INSERT INTO `immigrationaustralia_posts` VALUES (9,9,0,7,'State sponsorship - Victoria',0,221,'Jay',1365399834,'[size=medium]What is a State Migration Plan?[/size]\n\nThe Victorian Government has a formal agreement with the Australian Department of Immigration and Citizenship (DIAC), concerning the state nomination of skilled migrants to Victoria under the Skilled Nominated (190), Skilled - Sponsored (886) Graduate and Skilled Regional (489) visas. This agreement is called the State Migration Plan.\n\n[size=medium]Benefits[/size]\n[list]\n[*]    State Sponsorship offers the possibility of the applicants to obtain an answer regarding your visa very fast. Much, much faster than the common visa subclass 189.\n[*]    A visa holder can live and work permanently anywhere in Australia.\n[*]    Certain family members can be included in the application\n[/list]\n[size=medium]Obligations[/size]\n[list]\n[*]    If you are nominated by the State of Victoria, you must agree to remain in the state of Victoria for a period of [b]at least two years[/b]\n[*]    keep the State or Territory government informed of changes in address details before and after arrival\n[*]    be prepared to complete surveys and provide information as required\n[/list]\n[size=medium]Requirements[/size]\n\nApplications are by invitation only. To be invited to apply, a person must:\n[list]\n    [*]submit an Expression of Interest and be nominated\n    [*]your occupation must be listed on the State Nomination Occupation List for Victoria.\n    [*]have a current positive skills assessment for that occupation from the relevant assessing authority\n    [*]you must apply to DIAC for the Skilled Nominated (190) visa before your 50th birthday\n    [*]be able to score at least 60 on the points test\n    [*]include any other supporting documentation deemed relevant to the application\n    [*]submit an application online with Skilled Migration Victoria\n    [*]bring sufficient funds (see table below)\n    [*]you and your agent (if applicable) must read, understand and sign the Victorian nomination declaration in order to be considered for Victorian Government nomination.\n    [*]Detailed resume or curriculum vitae (CV)\n    [*]you must provide your IELTS assessment when you lodge your online application\n        [list][*]if you are required to provide an IELTS assessment, you must upload a scanned copy of your IELTS results as part of the online nomination application.\n[/list][/list]\n[size=medium]IELTS - necessary score[/size]\n\n    [list][*]score at least 6 on each test (0 points on that though)\n    [*]the test must not be older than 3 years\n    [*]--> If you are a citizen of the USA, UK, Canada, Republic of Ireland or New Zealand, you are not required to submit an IELTS assessment[/list]\n\n[size=medium]Finances[/size]\n\nYou must have adequate financial resources to support yourself and your dependants (if you have any) when you migrate to Victoria, or while you look for suitable employment. The table below shows the financial resources you must have access to, to support your nomination application.\nWe do not require evidence of these financial resources.\n\n[b]Onshore applicants[/b]\nAll applicants......................................................AUD required\nWorking in nominated occupation..............................20 000\nNot working in nominated occupation........................See offshore requirements\n\n[b]Offshore applicants[/b]\nNumber of dependants..........................................AUD required\nIndividual applicant...............................................30 000\n1........................................................................35 000\n2........................................................................40 000\n3........................................................................50 000\n4........................................................................60 000\n5........................................................................70 000\n6 or more............................................................80 000\n\n[size=medium]Declaration[/size]\n\nYou and your agent (if applicable) must read, understand and sign the Victorian nomination declaration in order to be considered for Victorian Government nomination.\n\nDownload the declaration form for the:\n\n[list][*]    [url=http://www.liveinvictoria.vic.gov.au/__data/assets/word_doc/0015/225051/SkilledDeclaration.doc]Skilled Nominated (190) and Skilled - Sponsored (886) visa[/url]\n[*]    [url=http://www.liveinvictoria.vic.gov.au/__data/assets/word_doc/0016/225052/RegionalDeclaration.doc]Skilled Regional (489) visa[/url]\n[/list]\nread and sign it, and upload it as part of your online sponsorship application.\n\n[size=medium]Detailed resume or curriculum vitae (CV)[/size]\n\nYour CV is a critical document used to assess your suitability for Victorian state nomination. It must provide evidence of your skills and work experience and a detailed, chronological list of all relevant employment.\n\nYou should take the time to ensure your CV is professionally presented, descriptive and provides our assessors and industry advisors with a comprehensive reflection of your skills, work readiness, employment history and work experience. You should explain any gaps in employment.\n\nYour CV should be three-to-four pages long and must include:\n[list]\n    [*]detailed descriptions of relevant tasks and responsibilities performed within all employment\n    [*]dates of employment (including month and year)\n    [*]dates of education and training.\n[/list]\nA relevant job offer from a Victorian employer can provide evidence of your work readiness and employability.\n\nYour application will be refused if your CV is too brief or does not include these details. If your application is refused, you must wait for six months after the application has been closed before you are eligible to reapply.\n\n[size=medium]About the required documents[/size]\n[list]\n    [*]all the documents that you send must be valid at the moment you are nominated\n    [*]provide certified copies of original documents - do not send original unless asked -\n    [*]accompany documents not in English with accredited English translations - original copies must be send though -\n    [*]do not send the documents by post\n[/list]\n[size=medium]Checklist[/size]\n\nWhen you lodge your online application, you must provide:\n[list]\n [*]   a detailed resume or CV\n  [*]  Victorian nomination declaration\n [*]   skills assessment (from 1st July 2012 a valid skills assessment is required at the time of lodging an application)\n  [*]  IELTS results (if applicable)\n  [*]  offer of employment (if applicable).\n[list]\nYou may be requested to provide additional documents if your application proceeds in the selection process. These documents can include:\n[list]\n    [*]trade qualification/certificates\n    [*]education transcripts\n    [*]evidence of licensing.\n[/list]\nIf these documents are requested, you will be given reasonable time to provide them.\n\nYou can submit scanned copies of these documents as part of your online nomination application. We do not require hard copies of any documents. Alternatively, you can email these documents tosmp.applications@liveinvictoria.vic.gov.au if you do not submit them with your online application.\nFees\n\nThere is [b]no[/b] application fee for Victorian nomination.\n\n[size=medium]Usefull links:[/size]\n    Official Migration website - Victoria: http://www.liveinvictoria.vic.gov.au/\n    State Sponsorship - Victoria: http://www.liveinvictoria.vic.gov.au/visas-and-immigrating/skilled-visas/skilled-nominated-visa-subclass-190\n    Frequently asked questions - Victoria: http://www.liveinvictoria.vic.gov.au/visas-and-immigrating/faqs-about-skilled-state-nomination-and-visas#nominated','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,221,1365408165,1,'05d26486b777127a80e1e8900981df87',''),(3,3,0,7,'The Stages of Immigration',0,1,'admin',1365321936,'The #stages of immigration have been extensively written about and the usual beginning point is to talk about the culture shock which occurs after immigration. This culture shock follows on directly as a result of changes which occur to one\'s value systems - to the new ideas in one\'s new country.\n\n The term \"culture shock\" was coined by Kalvero Oberg in a 1954 report published by Bobbs-Merrill, in which 5 distinct stages of culture shock were identified. All people experience the same feelings of strangeness when travelling to or living in another country and this process has a cause, symptoms and resolution.\n\n[size=large]1. Honeymoon Phase. [/size]\n\n Most people begin with great expectations and a positive mind-set. There is excitement, new sights, new smells, new tastes and the early problems are experienced as quaint - as part of the newness - anything new is intriguing and exciting. And, anyway, there are more pressing problems to deal with, like opening bank accounts, getting drivers licences, finding schools, doctors, dentists, gynaecologists. These are usually handled with the accompanying euphoria of having overcome each of these first hurdles successfully.\n\n[size=large]2. Rejection Phase. \n[/size]\n The honeymoon phase comes to an end as the newcomer has to deal with transportation problems (buses that don\'t come on time), shopping problems (can\'t buy their favourite foods or soaps or whatever) or communication problems (just what does \'Norny-norny-norn mean? (1999). What does \"See ya\' later\"/\'No worries mate\' really mean?). Little things come up but it may start to seem like people somehow no longer care about your problems. They may help, but they don\'t seem to understand your concern over what they see as small problems. You might even start to think that the people in your new country don\'t like newcomers and often you may begin to feel aggressive and start to complain about the new culture/country - \'Australians are \' \', or \'The system is \'\'. It is important to recognize that these feelings are real and can become acute. This phase is a crisis phase in the \'disease\' of culture shock and is called the \"rejection\" phase precisely because it is at this point that the newcomer starts to reject the host country, complaining about and noticing only the bad things that bother them. At this stage the newcomer either gets stronger and stays, or gets weaker and goes home (physically, mentally or both).\n\n[size=large]3. Regression Phase.[/size]\n\n If you have struggled with phase 2, you may find yourself moving into regression - moving backward - and in this phase of culture shock, you spend much of your time speaking your own language, watching videos from your home country, eating food from home. You may also notice that you are moving in social circles which are exclusively made up of people from your own background and you don\'t want to meet locals. You may spend most of this time complaining about the new country/culture and its strange and senseless ways. Also in the regression phase, you may only remember the good things about your home country which may suddenly seem marvellously wonderful; all the difficulties that you had there are forgotten and you may find yourself wondering why you ever left. You may now only remember your home country as a wonderful place in which nothing ever went wrong for you. Of course, this is not true, but an illusion created by your culture shock crisis.\n\n[size=large]4. Recovery Phase or At-Ease-At-Last Phase: [/size]\n\n If you survive the third stage successfully, you will move into the fourth stage of culture shock. In this stage you become more comfortable with the language and you also feel more comfortable with the customs of your new country. You can now move around without a feeling of anxiety. You still have problems with some of the social cues and you may still not understand everything people say (especially idioms) or do. However, you are now much better adjusted to the new culture and you start to realize that no country is that much better than another - it is just different lifestyles and different ways to deal with the problems of life. With this new adjustment, you accept the food, drinks, habits and customs of the new country, and you may even find yourself preferring some things in the new country, to things at home. You have now understood that there are different ways to live your life and that no way is really better than another, just different. Finally, you have become comfortable in the new place - it\'s not so bad. Most importantly, your sense of humour will have returned and you find you are able to look at yourself and laugh.\n\n[size=large]5. Reverse Culture Shock or Return Culture Shock[/size]\n\n This occurs when you return home after a long stay abroad and does not concern us here.\n\n Generally speaking, it is important to remember that not everyone experiences all the phases of culture shock. In addition, you can experience all of them at different times: you might experience the regression phase before the rejection phase, etc. You might even experience the regression phase on Monday, the at-ease phase on Tuesday, the honeymoon phase on Wednesday, and the rejection phase again on Thursday. What will Friday be like?\n\n Another interesting thing about culture shock is that there are routinely not one but two low points, and even more interestingly, they will accommodate themselves to the amount of time you intend to spend in the host country - are you a visitor or an immigrant? How long will culture shock last? That varies depending upon where you came from, how different the cultures are, your support systems and so on, but it also depends to some extent on you and your resiliency. You can expect a let-up after the first dip, but be prepared for the second downturn which may or may not occur.','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,1,1365322096,1,'e2ef86fccd8d9447527873bcb1041ec6',''),(4,4,0,7,'What is a State Migration Plan?',0,221,'Jay',1365337987,'The NSW Government has a formal agreement with the Australian Department of Immigration and Citizenship (DIAC), concerning the state nomination of skilled migrants to New South Wales under the Skilled Nominated (190), Skilled - Sponsored (886) Graduate and Skilled Regional (489) visas. This agreement is called the State Migration Plan.\r\n\r\n[size=medium]Benefits[/size]\r\n\r\nState Sponsorship offers the possibility of the applicants to obtain an answer regarding your visa very fast. Much, much faster than the common visa subclass 189.\r\n[list][*]A visa holder can live and work permanently anywhere in Australia.\r\n[*]Certain family members can be included in the application[/list]\r\n\r\n[size=medium]Obligations[/size]\r\n\r\n[list][*]If you are nominated by the State of New South Wales, you must agree to remain in the state of New South Wales for a period of at least two years\r\n[*]keep the government of New South Wales informed of changes in address details before and after arrival\r\n[*]be prepared to complete surveys and provide information as required[/list]\r\n\r\n[size=medium]Requirements[/size]\r\n\r\nApplications are by invitation only. To be invited to apply, a person must:\r\n[list][*]submit an Expression of Interest and be nominated\r\n[*]your occupation must be listed on the State Nomination Occupation List for NSW.\r\n[*]have a current positive skills assessment for that occupation from the relevant assessing authority\r\n[*]you must apply to DIAC for the Skilled Nominated (190) visa before your 50th birthday\r\n[*]be able to score at least 60 on the points test\r\n[*]a detalied C.V.\r\n[*]include any other supporting documentation deemed relevant to the application\r\n[*]submit an application online with Skilled Migration New South Wales\r\n[*]Applicants must sit the International English Language Testing System (IELTS) and score at least a six (6) on each of the four bands (Writing, Speaking, Listening, Reading).\r\n[list][*]Certain occupations require a higher standard of English in order to obtain a positive skill assessment. Please refer to the [url=http://www.immi.gov.au/asri/]assessing authorities\' English language requirements.[/url][/list][/list]\r\n\r\n[size=medium]IELTS - necessary score[/size]\r\n\r\n[list][*]score at least 6 on each of the four bands\r\n[*]If you are a citizen of the USA, UK, Canada, Republic of Ireland or New Zealand, you are not required to submit an IELTS assessment\r\n[*]the IELTS test must not be older than 2 years[/list]\r\n\r\n[size=medium]About the required documents[/size]\r\n\r\n[list][*]all the documents that you send must be valid at the moment you are nominated\r\n[*]provide certified copies of original documents - do not send original unless asked -\r\n[*]accompany documents not in English with accredited English translations - original copies must be send though -\r\n[*]do must send all your documents by post as the state of NSW does not accept online applications at the current time[/list]\r\n\r\n[size=medium]Checklist[/size]\r\n\r\nWhen you lodge your online application, you must provide:\r\n[list][*]NSW forms 1, 2, 3 and 4\r\n[*]a detailed resume or CV\r\n[*]New South Wales nomination declaration\r\n[*]skills assessment (from 1st July 2012 a valid skills assessment is required at the time of lodging an application)\r\n[*]Bio page of passport and existing Australian visa (if applicable)\r\n[*]IELTS score\r\n[*]emplyment references\r\n[*]qualifications\r\n[*][list][b]OPTIONAL[/b] but reccomended\r\n[*]letters of reference\r\n[*]letters of appointment (contracts of appointments)\r\n[*]Payroll records[/list][/list]\r\n\r\nYou may be requested to provide additional documents if your application proceeds in the selection process. These documents can include:\r\n[list][*]trade qualification/certificates\r\n[*]education transcripts\r\n[*]evidence of licensing[/list]\r\n\r\nIf these documents are requested, you will be given reasonable time to provide them.\r\n\r\nAll the required documents must be translated (if not in English), certified and dated.\r\n\r\nYou must submit the stamped form together with certified copies of your supporting documents. Please do not provide originals as these will not be returned to you.\r\n\r\n[size=medium]Fees[/size]\r\n\r\nThe following non-refundable application fees must be paid by bank cheque or money order payable to Industry & Investment NSW and enclosed with your application.\r\n\r\nA fee of $330 including GST is payable. Applications received from offshore applicants are from the GST component. The fees for these applications will be $300.00.\r\n\r\n[size=medium]Where to send all the documents\r\n[/size]\r\n[b]Manager, Skilled Migration[/b]\r\nNSW Trade & Investment\r\nLevel 47 MLC Centre\r\n19 Martin Place\r\nSydney NSW 2000\r\nAustralia\r\n\r\nor\r\n\r\nGPO Box 5477\r\nSydney NSW 2001\r\nAustralia\r\n\r\n[size=medium]Outcome[/size]\r\nYou will be sent a result letter that will advise the outcome of your application. If your application is successful, your application form will be stamped and signed by an authorised officer from NSW Trade & Investment.\r\n\r\nBusiness New South Wales: http://www.business.nsw.gov.au/\r\nSkilled Sponsored - direct link: http://www.business.nsw.gov.au/live-and-work-in-nsw/visa-and-migration/skilled-sponsored-migration','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'4c43a21d5e1afb0a450488c8ed783890',''),(5,5,0,7,'UNIT GROUP 2613 SOFTWARE AND APPLICATIONS PROGRAMMERS',0,221,'Jay',1365341377,'In Australia and New Zealand:\n\nMost occupations in this unit group have a level of skill commensurate with a bachelor degree or higher qualification. At least five years of relevant experience and/or relevant vendor certification may substitute for the formal qualification. In some instances relevant experience and/or on-the-job training may be required in addition to the formal qualification (ANZSCO Skill Level 1).\n\n[size=small]Tasks Include:[/size]\n[list][*]researching, consulting, analysing and evaluating system program needs \n[*]identifying technology limitations and deficiencies in existing systems and associated processes, procedures and methods \n[*]testing, debugging, diagnosing and correcting errors and faults in an applications programming language within established testing protocols, guidelines and quality standards to ensure programs and applications perform to specification \n[*]writing and maintaining program code to meet system requirements, system designs and technical specifications in accordance with quality accredited standards \n[*]writing, updating and maintaining technical program, end user documentation and operational procedures \n[*]providing advice, guidance and expertise in developing proposals and strategies for software design activities such as financial evaluation and costings for recommending software purchases and upgrades.[/list]\n\n[size=small]Occupations[/size]:\n[list][*]261311 Analyst Programmer \n[*]261312 Developer Programmer \n[*]261313 Software Engineer \n[*]261399 Software and Applications Programmers nec[/list]\n\n[size=small] 261311 ANALYST PROGRAMMER[/size]\n[b]Alternative Title:[/b] Programmer Analyst\nAnalyses user needs, produces requirements documentation and system plans, and encodes, tests, debugs, maintains and documents programs and applications.\nSkill Level: 1\n\n 261312 DEVELOPER PROGRAMMER\nAlternative Titles:Applications Developer \nICT Developer \nICT Programmer\nInterprets specifications, technical designs and flow charts, builds, maintains and modifies the code for software applications, constructs technical specifications from a business functional model, and tests and writes technical documentation.\nSkill Level: 1\n\n[size=x-small]Specialisations[/size]:\n\n[list][*]Communications Programmer (Systems) \n[*]Database Developer \n[*]Database Programmer (Systems) \n[*]Network Programmer \n[*]Software Developer \n[*]Software Programmer[/list]\n\n 261313 SOFTWARE ENGINEER\n[b]Alternative Titles[/b]: Software Architect \nSoftware Designer\nDesigns, develops, modifies, documents, tests, implements, installs and supports software applications and systems.\nSkill Level: 1\n\n[size=small]Specialisations[/size]:\n\nDatabase Designer \nSystems Architect\n\n 261399 SOFTWARE AND APPLICATIONS PROGRAMMERS NEC\nThis occupation group covers Software and Applications Programmers not elsewhere classified.\nSkill Level: 1\n\nOccupations in this group include: Software Tester','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,221,1365341428,1,'0063dc2e29a3585d9f74703bd13c240d',''),(6,6,0,7,'State sponsorship - Queensland',0,221,'Jay',1365347766,'[size=small]Benefits[/size]\r\n\r\n    State Sponsorship offers the possibility of the applicants to obtain an answer regarding your visa very fast. Much, much faster than the common visa subclass 189.\r\n    [list][*]A visa holder can live and work permanently anywhere in Australia.\r\n    [*]Certain family members can be included in the application[/list]\r\n\r\n[size=small]Obligations[/size]\r\n\r\n  [list][*]  If you are nominated by a State or Territory government, you need to agree to remain in Queensland for a period of at least two years\r\n [*]   keep the State or Territory government informed of changes in address details before and after arrival\r\n [*]  be prepared to complete surveys and provide information as required\r\n[/list]\r\n[size=small]Requirements[/size]\r\n\r\nApplications are by invitation only. To be invited to apply, a person must:\r\n\r\n[list][*]    submit an Expression of Interest and be nominated\r\n    [*]have an occupation on Queensland\'s Skilled - Nominated (subclass 190) visa Eligible Skills List\r\n    [*]have a current positive skills assessment for that occupation from the relevant assessing authority\r\n    [*]be less than 50 years of age when the invitation is issued\r\n    [*]meet the English language requirements\r\n    [*]be able to score at least 60 on the points test\r\n    [*]include a copy of a detailed CV\r\n    [*]be assessed by Skilled and Business Migration as being likely to provide a clear benefit to the Queensland economy\r\n    [*]include any other supporting documentation deemed relevant to the application\r\n    [*]have sufficient settlement funds (as cash) to cover potential long periods of unemployment[/list]\r\n\r\n[size=small]IELTS - necessary score[/size]\r\n\r\n    check the attached PDF with the occupation list (below) and you will see there the minimum score required for each occupation\r\n    [list][*]the test must not be older than 3 years[/list]\r\n\r\n[size=small]About the required documents[/size]\r\n\r\n [list][*]   all the documents that you send must be valid at the moment you are nominated\r\n    [*]provide certified copies of original documents (do not send original unless asked)\r\n    [*]accompany documents not in English with accredited English translations[/list]\r\n\r\n[size=small]Required documents[/size]\r\n\r\n    [list][*]a detailed CV\r\n [*]   have a current positive skills assessment for that occupation from the relevant assessing authority\r\n [*]   passport page\r\n [*]   IELTS results page - not older than 3 years\r\n [*]   references and recommendations from your workplace - see booklet 6\r\n [*]   qualifications, certifications, etc, that will help your application\r\n [*] [list][b]Optional[/b] but highly recommended\r\n          [*]  payslips\r\n           [*] work contracts\r\n           [*] recomandations letters (certified, translated, dated, etc...)[/list][/list]\r\n\r\n[size=small]How fast will the application be processed ?[/size]\r\n\r\nBetween 3 and 4 weeks.','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'b55f51fa1d46e9be88f740457285e3b0',''),(7,7,0,7,'State sponsorship - Western Australia',0,221,'Jay',1365349263,'[size=small]Benefits[/size]\r\n\r\nState Sponsorship offers the possibility of the applicants to obtain an answer regarding your visa very fast. Much, much faster than the common visa subclass 189.\r\n[list][*]A visa holder can live and work permanently anywhere in Australia.\r\n[*]Certain family members can be included in the application[/list]\r\n\r\n[size=small]Obligations[/size]\r\n\r\nIf you are nominated by the State of Western Australia, you will need to agree to \r\n[list][*]remain there for a period of at least two years\r\n[*]keep the State or Territory government informed of changes in address details before and after arrival\r\n[*]be prepared to complete surveys and provide information as required\r\n[/list]\r\n[size=small]Requirements[/size]\r\n\r\nApplications are by invitation only. To be invited to apply, a person must:\r\n[list][*]submit an Expression of Interest and be nominated\r\n[*]have an occupation on Western Australia\'s Skilled - Nominated (subclass 190) visa Eligible Skills List\r\n[*]have a current positive skills assessment for that occupation from the relevant assessing authority\r\n[*]be less than 49 years of age when the invitation is issued - it takes about 8 weeks till the decision is issued\r\n[*]meet the English language requirements\r\n[*]be able to score at least 6 on the points test\r\n[*]include any other supporting documentation deemed relevant to the application\r\n[*]have sufficient settlement funds (as cash) to cover potential long periods of unemployment\r\n[*]submit an application online with Skilled Migration Western Australia and pay a non refundable $200 application fee\r\n[*]if required, an offer of employment emailed to migration@dtwd.wa.gov.au  after submitting an online application\r\n[*]bring sufficient funds (for at least three months) into the State to cover settlement costs (successful applicants)[/list]\r\n\r\nfor visa subclass 487, provide evidence of three job opportunities (such as links to online advertisements for job vacancies) in your nominated occupation and region;\r\n\r\n[size=small]IELTS - necessary score[/size]\r\n\r\nscore at least 6 on each test (0 points on that though)\r\nthe test must not be older than 3 years\r\n\r\n[size=small]About the required documents[/size]\r\n\r\n[list][*]all the documents that you send must be valid at the moment you are nominated\r\n[*]provide certified copies of original documents - do not send original unless asked -\r\n[*]accompany documents not in English with accredited English translations - original copies must be send though -\r\n[*]do not send the documents by post, those will be destroyed[/list]\r\n\r\n[size=small]Required documents\r\n[/size]\r\n[list][*]have a current positive skills assessment for that occupation from the relevant assessing authority\r\n[*]passport page\r\n[*]IELTS results page - not older than 3 years\r\n[*]references and recommendations from your workplace - see booklet 6 (below)\r\n[*]qualifications, certifications, etc, that will help your application\r\n[*][b]optional[/b] but highly recommended\r\n[list][*]payslips\r\n[*]work contracts\r\n[*]recommendations letters (certified, translated, dated, etc...)[/list][/list]\r\n\r\n[size=small]Checklist[/size]\r\n\r\n[list][*]copy of the assessment decision\r\n[*]copy of the passport\r\n[*]copy of IELTS results\r\n[*][b]optional[/b]: contracts/employment letters from your work or ex employers in the last 3 years[/list]\r\n\r\n[size=small]How fast will the application be processed ?[/size]\r\n\r\nIt takes about 8 weeks\r\n\r\n[size=small]Useful Links:[/size]\r\nMigration Western Australia - official website: http://www.migration.wa.gov.au/\r\nList of occupation - western Australia: http://www.migration.wa.gov.au/skilledmigration/Pages/Occupationsindemand.aspx','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'501539be2e3a7724a13c01c9a7b63700',''),(8,8,0,7,'Children born in Australia, what status do they have ?',0,221,'Jay',1365354113,'I will presume that he who had emigrated is a permanent resident of Australia (eg: visa subclass 189 & 190).\r\n\r\nIf the baby was born in Australia, and at least one of his parents is an Australian citizen or has a permanent resident status, the newborn will receive Australian citizenship. The newborn will  not need any visa to stay in Australia.\r\n\r\nIf the newborn was born outside Australia and at least one of the parents is an Australian citizen, the child will receive Australian citizenship by descendant.\r\n\r\nIf the baby is born outside Australian and none of the parents is an Australian citizen, the baby will have no Australian status and as such he will need a visa to enter Australia and stay there.\r\n\r\nWhat happens if the parents received a permanent visa but they did not validate it ?\r\n\r\nValidation means that the parents need to enter Australia before the deadline stipulated in the documents when the parents received the visa.\r\nIf you have been granted a permanent visa but it is not valid and you are not in Australia and in the meantime your baby has been born, he or she will not automatically receive a visa. DIAC must be informed about this change in circumstances and the new baby will have to be sponsored by you to receive a visa\r\nThe procedure is relative simple and should not take more than 10 - 12 weeks until your baby has the visa.\r\nRemember: for your newborn to receive visa he must have a passport','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'285c79394d02ab940c39b967014283b6',''),(10,10,0,7,'Visa Subclass 189 - Skilled independent',0,221,'Jay',1365412816,'This visa is also called Skilled Independent visa and is the most common used visa. The visa subclass 189 targets those who knows English best and be able to emigrate wherever in Australia as it has no strings attached (location wise). This visa does not need any sponsorship from any relative, state or territory.\r\n\r\n[size=medium]How ?[/size]\r\n\r\nApplying for this visa can be done only through SkillSelect website\r\nThe applicant(s) must be invited to apply for this visa\r\nAfter the invitation has been made, the applicant or applicants have merely 60 days to send all the documents for the claimed points.\r\n\r\n[size=medium]Eligibility[/size]\r\n[list]\r\n[*]be less than 50 years of age when the invitation is issued\r\n[*]have an occupation that is on the relevant skilled occupation list\r\n[*]meet the English language requirements\r\n[list][*]If one is born or has a passport issued from a English speaking country (UK, USA, Canada, etc), one is exempt from IELTS\r\nyou need to take only the general test UNLESS otherwise advised by your skills assessing authority. That means if your assessing authority tells you that you need academic IELTS or other, do that, if not do not take academic as it will not be considered by DIAC.\r\n[*]all the secondary applicants who are 18 or over must take the IELTS exam and achieve a score of at least 4.5 on each of the four components of speaking, reading, listening and writing. IF they don\'t achieve a score of at least 4.5 on each component, they must pay the second installment\r\n[*]IELTS is valid for 36 months[/list]\r\n[*]have a suitable skills assessment for that occupation\r\n[list][*]must have a work experience of at least 3 years in the last 10 years before applying (1 year for Australian work experience)[/list]\r\n[*]must be in good health\r\n[*]have no criminal record (serious offences)\r\n[*]be able to score at least 60 on the points test\r\n[/list]\r\n[size=medium]Conditions & Validity[/size]\r\n\r\n[list][*]there are no conditions for this visa\r\n[*]if he or she obtains visa 189 (Skilled Independent), all the secondary applicants have the right to live and work in Australia indefinitely, in any field, anywhere. Well, [*]Australian laws must be obeyed\r\n[*]the applicant(s) can travel outside Australia for 5 years after visa grant. After this period the applicant(s) can stay in Australia indefinetly, but if one travels outside [*]Australia he must apply for a visa once again. During those 5 years after grant, you can obtain Australian citizenship\r\n[/list]\r\n[size=medium]Family members[/size]\r\n\r\n[list][*]you can include in your visa\r\n[*]husband\r\n[*]fiancee\r\n[*]life partner (same sex included)\r\n[*]dependent child (including step child(s))\r\n[*]other dependents - ex: dependent parents\r\n[/list]\r\n[size=medium]Costs[/size]\r\n[list]\r\nThe tax is paid only once, when you apply for the visa, it must be paid before visa can be granted\r\n[*]1\'st installment  - The charge for lodging this visa application is AUD3060. This payment covers you and all dependent family members included in your application OR\r\n[*]2\'nd installment -  only to the people on your application who have less than functional English and are 18 years of age or older. The charge is AUD4250 per person. It must be paid before a visa can be granted. The payment covers up to three years of English language instruction through the Adult Migrant English Program\r\n[/list]You must take into account the taxes and costs for: sending documents to Australia if needed, medicals, criminal records, translations, etc...\r\n\r\nCheck the [url=http://www.immi.gov.au/skills/skillselect/index/visas/subclass-189/#sub-heading-2]official website[/url] for #taxes\r\n\r\nSkillSelect: http://skillselect.gov.au/','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'1cebe42636934c468b1fb97bf50b51d2',''),(11,11,0,7,'Points test table 2012 - 2013',0,221,'Jay',1365414589,'[table=80][tr][td]Ageat time of invitation[/td][td]18–24 (inclusive)[/td][td]25[/td][/tr][tr][td][/td][td]25–32 (inclusive)[/td][td]30[/td][/tr][tr][td][/td][td]33–39 (inclusive)[/td][td]25[/td][/tr][tr][td][/td][td]40–44 (inclusive)[/td][td]15[/td][/tr][tr][td][/td][td]45–49 (inclusive)[/td][td]0[/td][/tr][tr][td]English language abilityat time of invitation[/td][td]Competent English—IELTS 6 / OET B[/td][td]0[/td][/tr][tr][td][/td][td]Proficient English—IELTS 7 / OET B[/td][td]10[/td][/tr][tr][td][/td][td]Superior English—IELTS 8 / OET A[/td][td]20[/td][/tr][tr][td]Skilled employmentat time of invitation[/td][td][b]Skilled employment outside Australia[/b]\n\nAt least three but less than five years (of past 10 years)[/td][td]5[/td][/tr][tr][td]Only 20 points can be awarded for any combination of overseas and Australian skilled employment[/td][td]At least five but less than eight years (of past 10 years)[/td][td]10[/td][/tr][tr][td]Overseas employment in nominated skilled occupation or a closely related skilled occupation[/td][td]At least eight and up to 10 years (of past 10 years)[/td][td]15[/td][/tr][tr][td]Australian employment in nominated skilled occupation or a closely related skilled occupation[/td][td][b]Skilled employment in Australia[/b]\n\nAt least one but less than three years (of past 10 years)[/td][td]5[/td][/tr][tr][td][/td][td]At least three but less than five years (of past 10 years)[/td][td]10[/td][/tr][tr][td][/td][td]At least five but less than eight years (of past 10 years)[/td][td]15[/td][/tr][tr][td][/td][td]At least eight and up to 10 years (of past 10 years)[/td][td]20[/td][/tr][tr][td]Educational qualificationsat time of invitation[/td][td]Doctorate from an Australian educational institution or other Doctorate of a recognised standard[/td][td]20[/td][/tr][tr][td][/td][td]At least a Bachelor degree, including a Bachelor degree with Honours or Masters, from an Australian educational institution or other degree of a recognised standard[/td][td]15[/td][/tr][tr][td][/td][td]Diploma or trade qualification completed in Australia, or qualification or award of recognised standard[/td][td]10[/td][/tr][tr][td]Australian study requirementsat time of invitation[/td][td]One or more degrees, diplomas or trade qualifications awarded by an Australian educational institution and meet the Australian Study Requirement[/td][td]5[/td][/tr][tr][td]Other factorsat time of invitation[/td][td]Credentialled community language qualifications[/td][td]5[/td][/tr][tr][td][/td][td]Study in regional Australia or a low population growth metropolitan area (excluding distance education[/td][td]5[/td][/tr][tr][td][/td][td]Partner skill qualifications[/td][td]5[/td][/tr][tr][td][/td][td]Professional Year in Australia for at least 12 months in the four years before the day you were invited[/td][td]5[/td][/tr][tr][td]Nomination/sponsorshipat time of invitation[/td][td]Nomination by state or territory government (visa subclass 190 only)[/td][td]5[/td][/tr][tr][td][/td][td]Nomination by state or territory government or sponsorship by an eligible family member, to reside and work in a specified/designated area (visa subclass 489 only)[/td][td]10[/td][/tr][/table]','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,221,1365414663,1,'8311ce46dab52ac6120f19e08d4583dd',''),(12,12,0,7,'State sponsorship - Tasmania 189 visa',0,221,'Jay',1365415840,'[size=medium]What is a State Migration Plan?[/size]\r\n\r\nThe Tasmanian Government has a formal agreement with the Australian Department of Immigration and Citizenship (DIAC), concerning the state nomination of skilled migrants to Tasmania under the Skilled Nominated (190), Skilled - Sponsored(886) Graduate and Skilled Regional (489) visas. This agreement is called the State Migration Plan.\r\n\r\n[size=medium]Benefits[/size]\r\n[list]\r\n[*]State Sponsorship offers the possibility of the applicants to obtain an answer regarding your visa very fast. Much, much faster than the common visa subclass 189.\r\n[*]A visa holder can live and work permanently anywhere in Australia after the 2 year period.\r\n[*]Certain family members can be included in the application\r\n[/list]\r\n[size=medium]Obligations[/size]\r\n\r\nIf you are nominated by the State of Tasmania, you must agree to \r\n[list][*]remain in the state of Tasmania for a period of at least two years\r\n[*]keep the government of Tasmania informed of changes in address details before and after arrival\r\n[*]be prepared to complete surveys and provide information as required\r\n[/list]\r\n[size=medium]Requirements[/size]\r\n\r\nApplications are by invitation only. To be invited to apply, a person must:\r\n[list][*]submit an Expression of Interest and be nominated\r\n[*]your occupation must be listed on the State Nomination Occupation List for Tasmania.\r\n[*]have a current positive skills assessment for that occupation from the relevant assessing authority\r\n[*]you must apply to DIAC for the Skilled Nominated (190) visa\r\n[*]be able to score at least 60 on the points test\r\n[*]a detalied C.V.\r\n[*]include any other supporting documentation deemed relevant to the application\r\n[*]submit an application online with Skilled Migration Tasmania\r\n[*]Applicants must sit the International English Language Testing System (IELTS) and score at least a six (6) on each of the four bands (Writing, Speaking, Listening, Reading). [list][*]If you come from an English speaking country you are exempt from taking the IELTSexam\r\n[*]Certain occupations require a higher standard of English in order to obtain a positive skill assessment. Please refer to the assessing authorities\' English language requirements.[/list][/list]\r\n\r\n[size=medium]IELTS - necessary score[/size]\r\n[list]\r\n[*]score at least 6 on each of the four bands\r\n[*]If you are a citizen of the USA, UK, Canada, Republic of Ireland or New Zealand, you are not required to submit an IELTS assessment\r\n[*]the IELTS test must not be older than 2 years[/list]\r\n\r\n[size=medium]About the required documents[/size]\r\n[list]\r\n[*]all the documents that you send must be valid at the moment you are nominated\r\n[*]provide certified copies of original documents - do not send original unless asked -\r\n[*]accompany documents not in English with accredited English translations - original copies must be send -[/list]\r\n\r\n[size=medium]Checklist[/size]\r\n\r\nWhen you lodge your online application, you must provide:\r\n[list][*]Tasmania form\r\n[*]a detailed resume or CV\r\n[*]Tasmania Goverment nomination declaration\r\n[*]skills assessment (from 1st July 2012 a valid skills assessment is required at the time of lodging an application)\r\n[*]Bio page of passport and existing Australian visa (if applicable)\r\n[*]IELTS score\r\n[*]emplyment references\r\n[*]qualifications\r\n[*](If applicant is offshore) sufficient transferrable assets to assist with relocation\r\n[*][list]OPTIONAL but reccomended\r\n[*]letters of reference\r\n[*]letters of appointment (contracts of appointments)\r\n[*]Payroll records[/list][/list]\r\n\r\nYou may be requested to provide additional documents if your application proceeds in the selection process. These documents can include:\r\n[list][*]trade qualification/certificates\r\n[*]education transcripts\r\n[*]evidence of licensing.[/list]\r\n\r\nIf these documents are requested, you will be given reasonable time to provide them.\r\n\r\nAll the required documents must be translated (if not in English), certified and dated.\r\n\r\nYou must submit the stamped form together with certified copies of your supporting documents. Please do not provide originals as these will not be returned to you.\r\n\r\n[size=medium]Commitment to Tasmania[/size]\r\n\r\nYou must provide evidence that you are intending to stay and live in Tasmania, and, as such you will have to provide:\r\n[list][*]job research for your nominated job: employment opportunity, license requirements, registration requirements for your skills, etc\r\n[*]if you ever been to Tasmania show it: pictures, information, plane tickets, etc\r\n[*]if you have family, friends (even social network) you can tell the authorites to demonstrate your commitment[/list]\r\n\r\n[size=medium]Fees[/size]\r\n\r\nCurrently there are no fees for Tasmania State Migration Plan\r\n\r\n[size=medium]Outcome[/size]\r\n\r\nYou will be sent a result letter that will advise the outcome of your application. If your application is successful, your application form will be stamped and signed by an authorised officer.\r\n\r\n[b]Useful links:[/b]\r\n\r\nMigration Tasmania: http://www.migration.tas.gov.au/\r\nApplication Forms: http://www.migration.tas.gov.au/forms/apply/skilled','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'dce084ffb0a8cc53f902f1332465a3b2',''),(13,13,0,7,'Vetassess assessment process',0,221,'Jay',1365417608,'[size=large]Assessment process[/size]\r\n\r\n[size=medium]1. Get information[/size]\r\n\r\nOur helpful and friendly staff will provide you with information about the assessment and the relevant documentation you need to proceed with your application. We will provide you with a personalised service to meet your needs and will help you with a self assessment guide, application forms and fee information. We will also assist you with ideas for evidence to put in your portfolio to submit with your application.\r\n\r\nContact us on +61 3 9655 4815 or 4877\r\n\r\n[size=medium]2. Submit your portfolio of evidence for assessment[/size]\r\n\r\nA qualified assessor will review the evidence you provide with your application and will contact you to discuss your assessment.\r\n\r\nDuring this discussion, your assessor will:\r\n[list][*]advise you if further evidence is required\r\n[*]arrange a time and date to conduct your assessment\r\n[*]arrange a venue for the assessment\r\n[*]explain what your assessment will involve.\r\n[/list]\r\n[size=medium]3. Participate in the assessment - interview and/or practical assessment[/size]\r\n\r\nIn addition to the portfolio of evidence that you submit with your application, you will be asked to attend an assessment session with an assessor. This may involve a detailed interview, a visit to your workplace, a practical assessment conducted at a workshop or a combination of all of these. The assessment will give you the opportunity to demonstrate your skills and knowledge of the occupation.\r\n\r\nFor assessments in trade occupations, you may need to bring suitable clothing, protective gear and any tools necessary to demonstrate your skills. Your assessor will advise you of the requirements.\r\n\r\n[size=medium]4. Receive assessment result and certificate[/size]\r\n\r\nIf you are successful in meeting all of the requirements you will receive a nationally recognised Australian qualification in your occupation and a record of the units of competency you have attained.\r\n\r\nIf you do not meet all of the requirements, you will receive a Statement of Attainment recording the units of competency you have attained. You can then come back at a later stage to be reassessed and gain your qualification after gaining more experience or undertaking further training.\r\n\r\n[size=large]Applying for assessment[/size]\r\n\r\nTo have your skills assessed for national recognition, you need to submit an application form.\r\n\r\nFollow these simple steps:\r\nDownload and complete an A[url=http://download.vetassess.com.au/forms/competency_assessment/Competency%20Assessment%20Application%20Form.pdf]pplication for Competency Assessment[/url].\r\nGather all [url=http://www.vetassess.com.au/assess_my_skills/ns_required_documents.cfm]required documents.[/url]\r\nSend your completed application form, required documents and a[url=http://www.vetassess.com.au/assess_my_skills/ns_fees_payment.cfm]ssessment fees[/url] to VETASSESS.\r\n[table=85][tr][td]Post[/td][td]Courier[/td][/tr][tr][td]Skills Recognition – NationalCompetency assessment serviceGPO Box 2752Melbourne VIC 3001[/td][td]Skills Recognition – NationalCompetency assessment serviceLevel 5, 478 Albert StreetEast Melbourne VIC 3002[/td][/tr][/table]\r\n\r\n[size=medium]Required documents\r\n[/size]\r\nTo have your skills assessed for national recognition there are a number of documents that you must submit with your application.\r\n\r\nPlease note:\r\n[list][*]Applications missing the required documents will be delayed.\r\n[*]We will contact you for additional documentation, if required.\r\n[*]Documents will not be returned.[/list]\r\n[table=100][tr][td]Document[/td][td]Notes[/td][/tr][tr][td]Application form[/td][td]Download the [url=http://download.vetassess.com.au/forms/competency_assessment/Competency%20Assessment%20Application%20Form.pdf]Application for Competency Assessment[/url]Forms should be completed, dated and signed[/td][/tr][tr][td]2 recent photographs[/td][td]Must be passport size, certified and dated (taken within last three months)[/td][/tr][tr][td]Identity &amp; citizenship documents – Australian driver\'s licence, relevant passport pages (including relevant visas)[/td][td]Must be [url=http://www.vetassess.com.au/certifying_document/certifying_documents.cfm]certified[/url] (passport page must show name, photo and date of birth)[/td][/tr][tr][td]Any training qualifications or certificates[/td][td]Must be [url=http://www.vetassess.com.au/certifying_document/certifying_documents.cfm]certified[/url][/td][/tr][tr][td]Academic record/results[/td][td]Must be [url=http://www.vetassess.com.au/certifying_document/certifying_documents.cfm]certified[/url],, providing details of the subjects/modules or units completed and the date of completion[/td][/tr][tr][td]Evidence of activity/experience[/td][td]Read more about [url=http://www.vetassess.com.au/assess_my_skills/ns_required_documents.cfm#1]suggested evidence[/url][/td][/tr][tr][td]Change of name evidence[/td][td](if applicable)[/td][/tr][tr][td]Assessment fee[/td][td]Read more about [url=http://www.vetassess.com.au/assess_my_skills/ns_fees_payment.cfm]fees &amp; payments[/url][/td][/tr][/table]\r\n\r\n[size=large]Suggested evidence[/size]\r\n\r\nYou should select evidence that shows that you are able to do the work related to your occupation. VETASSESS staff and your assessor will help you to identify relevant and suitable evidence for your portfolio. A portfolio is a collection of evidence that helps your assessor to assess your competency within your occupation.\r\n\r\nExamples of evidence you may include in your portfolio are:\r\n[list][*][b]certificates[/b]: certified copies of qualifications, diplomas, statements of attendance or results from any relevant course\r\n[*][b]trade documents or related details[/b]: evidence of trade training undertaken in Australia or overseas, including training undertaken with the Australian Defence Forces\r\n[*][b]licences or registration documents[/b]: such as using particular equipment, OH&S requirements\r\n[*][b]references[/b]: from employers, clients, community groups etc; they can be written or supplied over the telephone\r\n[*][b]proof of employment[/b]: such as pay slips, group certificates or computer records\r\n[*][b]products[/b]: samples of work using the real product or photographs\r\n[*][b]videos[/b]: showing actual use of machinery or workplace activity\r\n[*][b]course syllabus[/b]: syllabus or structure of courses you have undertaken\r\n[*][b]testimonials[/b]: statements from employers, supervisors and others about the quality of your work or study skills\r\n[*][b]log books or diaries[/b]: related to your employment\r\n[*][b]newsletters[/b]: articles explaining your work function or how the department in which you work operates.\r\n[/list]\r\n[size=medium]Hospitality Trades[/size]\r\n\r\n[b]First aid requirements [/b]\r\n\r\nTo receive a qualification you will need to provide evidence of a recent first aid certificate for the following compulsory unit;\r\n\r\n[u]HLTFA301B Apply First Aid[/u]\r\n\r\nIf you do not hold recent certification of your first aid skills and are successful in all other aspects of the skills assessment, you will be issued with a Statement of Attainment and will need to undertake a training program to achieve this unit.\r\n\r\n[size=medium]Painting & decorating[/size]\r\n\r\n[b]Licensing requirements [/b]\r\nTo receive a qualification you will need to provide evidence of a licence or statement of attainment for the following compulsory units;\r\n[table=85][tr][td]Unit of competency[/td][td]Licence required[/td][/tr][tr][td]CPCCCM3001B Operate elevated work platforms[/td][td]Elevated work platform association of Australia[/td][/tr][tr][td]CPCCCM2008A Erect and dismantle restricted height scaffolding[/td][td]Licence to perform high risk work[/td][/tr][/table]\r\n[b]Further Information[/b]\r\nIf you would like further information about units of competence that make up this qualification, please refer to http://www.training.gov.au.\r\n\r\n[size=large]Fees & payment[/size]\r\n[size=medium]Government funded[/size]\r\nIf you live in Victoria and meet the following requirements, you may be eligible for government funding.\r\n\r\nMeet one of the following citizen/residency status:\r\n[list][*]Australian citizen\r\n[*]Australian Permanent Resident (holder of a permanent visa)\r\n[*]holder of a Special Category Visa (sub-class 444, New Zealand citizen)\r\n[*]holder of a Temporary Protection Visa\r\n[*]East Timorese asylum seeker.\r\n[/list]\r\n\r\nAnd are the following:\r\n[list][*]20 years and older and \'upskilling\' by undertaking a course at a higher level than your existing qualification\r\n[*]You haven\'t begun and are not enrolled to begin two or more other government-subsidised courses in 2012. (This means that you can start no more than two government-subsidised courses in this calendar year)\r\n[*]You are not already doing two or more other government-subsidised courses. (This means that you can do no more than two government-subsidised courses at one time).\r\n[/list]\r\nIf you think you may be eligible for government funding please contact us to discuss on 03 9655 4877.\r\n\r\n[size=medium]Fee for service[/size]\r\n\r\nIf you are applying to have your skills assessed for national recognition, it is important you are aware of the fees incurred.\r\n\r\nIf you are applying from interstate, additional assessor travel fees may be required particularly if you are a regional area. For a practical assessment, the assessor travels to meet with you and to visit your workplace (if appropriate).\r\n\r\nFor information on all the qualifications available to you please go to http://www.training.gov.au\r\n[table=55][tr][td][b]Qualification[/b][/td][td][b]Fees* per person[/b][/td][/tr][tr][td]Certificate I &amp; II[/td][td]$850[/td][/tr][tr][td]Certificate III &amp; IV[/td][td]$1,500[/td][/tr][tr][td]Diploma / Advanced Diploma[/td][td]$1,500[/td][/tr][tr][td]Certificate III in Refrigeration &amp; Air conditioning (Licensed trade)[/td][td]$1,800[/td][/tr][/table]\r\n\r\n[b]Please note[/b]: Group discounts may apply\r\n[table=35][tr][td][b]Other services[/b][/td][td][b]Fee[/b][/td][/tr][tr][td]Re-assessment[/td][td]$600[/td][/tr][tr][td]Appeal[/td][td]$350[/td][/tr][tr][td]Re-issue of lost/destroyed certificates[/td][td]$75[/td][/tr][/table]\r\n\r\n[size=large]Reassessment, appeals & feedback[/size]\r\n[size=medium]Reassessment[/size]\r\n\r\nReassessment against the same qualification is offered within 12 months of the first assessment being completed. There are a number of ways that you can be reassessed. These include verification of on the job training or undertaking gap training. The fee when submitting an application for reassessment is $600.00.\r\n\r\n[size=medium]Appeals[/size]\r\n\r\nAn appeal can be lodged if you have a grievance regarding the assessment process, or fairness in the way you were treated. The fee is $350.00.\r\n\r\nIf you disagree with the outcome of the assessment, you can appeal on the following grounds:\r\n[list][*]the judgment was not made in accordance with the assessment plan\r\n[*]the VETASSESS competency assessment process was not followed\r\n[*]you believe that you were unfairly treated or discriminated against.[/list]\r\n\r\nPlease note:\r\n[list][*]applications for appeal must be lodged within 14 days of VETASSESS issuing advice on the initial assessment\r\n[*]fees are non-refundable\r\n[*]the outcome of the appeal is final.[/list]\r\n\r\n[size=medium]Reissue[/size]\r\n\r\nA reissue is a reprint of your assessment outcome with the current date. In cases where your certificate has been lost or destroyed we can reissue you with a new one. The fee when submitting an application for reissue is $75.00.\r\n\r\n[size=medium]Feedback & complaints[/size]\r\n\r\nIf you wish to provide feedback or make a complaint about the service provided by VETASSESS please click  [url=http://www.vetassess.com.au/about_vetassess/contact_us.cfm]here[/url]  using our online feedback page.\r\n\r\nAcknowledgement will be sent within 5 working days informing you of the person allocated to investigate your complaint. A complaint investigation form will be completed to record findings and recommendations. This will then formulate the written response to be issued within 10 working days.\r\n\r\nAll documentation will be filed in accordance with the [url=http://www.vetassess.com.au/download/offshore/VETASSESS_Complaints_Feedback_Handling_Policy.pdf?id=130820120939AM]VETASSESS Complaints/Feedback Handling Policy[/url] and complaint procedures consistent with the Standards for NVR Registered Training Organisations.\r\n\r\n[size=large]Download forms[/size]\r\nNational skills recognition\r\n\r\n[table=95][tr][td]Filename[/td][td]Type[/td][td]Size[/td][/tr][tr][td][url=http://download.vetassess.com.au/forms/competency_assessment/Competency%20Assessment%20Application%20Form.pdf?id=020220131213AM]Competency Assessment Application form[/url][/td][td]pdf[/td][td]95kb[/td][/tr][tr][td][url=http://download.vetassess.com.au/forms/competency_assessment/Explanatory_notes_competency.pdf?id=020220131213AM]Explanatory notes for Competency Assessment form[/url][/td][td]pdf[/td][td]88kb[/td][/tr][tr][td][url=http://download.vetassess.com.au/forms/competency_assessment/Request_for_Reissue.pdf?id=020220131213AM]Request for Re-issue form[/url][/td][td]pdf[/td][td]43kb[/td][/tr][tr][td][url=http://download.vetassess.com.au/forms/competency_assessment/Request_for_Reissue.pdf?id=020220131213AM]Request for Reassessment[/url][/td][td]pdf[/td][td]42kb[/td][/tr][tr][td][url=http://download.vetassess.com.au/forms/competency_assessment/Request_for_Reassessment.pdf?id=020220131213AM]Request for Appeal Application form[/url][/td][td]pdf[/td][td]83kb[/td][/tr][tr][td][url=http://download.vetassess.com.au/forms/competency_assessment/FM-SRN05_Request_for_Withdrawal.pdf?id=020220131213AM]Request for Withdrawal Application form[/url][/td][td]pdf[/td][td]73.9kb[/td][/tr][/table]\r\n\r\nVetassess official website: http://www.vetassess.com.au/index.cfm','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'eda5e5230d97da97f42fb2243ae570c1',''),(14,14,0,24,'Darwin Australia - filmed with a Canon 7D Video',0,221,'Jay',1365425869,'Http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6NlHMALYwDw&feature=youtu.be','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'c800b1cf20c7cf113bdaf1150b0bfb1f',''),(15,15,0,32,'Victorian public holidays 2013-2015',0,221,'Jay',1365426405,'[table=100][tr][td][b]Holiday[/b][/td][td]2013[/td][td]2014[/td][td]2015[/td][/tr][tr][td][b]New Year\'s Day[/b][/td][td]Tuesday 1 January[/td][td]Wednesday 1 January[/td][td]Thursday 1 January[/td][/tr][tr][td][b]Australia Day[/b][/td][td]Monday 28 January *substitute for Sat 26 January[/td][td]Monday 27 January *substitute for Sun 26 January[/td][td]Monday 26 January[/td][/tr][tr][td][b]Labour Day[/b][/td][td]Monday 11 March[/td][td]Monday 10 March[/td][td]Monday 9 March[/td][/tr][tr][td][b]Good Friday[/b][/td][td]Friday 29 March[/td][td]Friday 18 April[/td][td]Friday 3 April[/td][/tr][tr][td][b]Saturday before Easter Sunday[/b][/td][td]Saturday 30 March[/td][td]Saturday 19 April[/td][td]Saturday 4 April[/td][/tr][tr][td][b]Easter Monday[/b][/td][td]Monday 1 April[/td][td]Monday 21 April[/td][td]Monday 6 April[/td][/tr][tr][td][b]ANZAC Day[/b][/td][td]Thursday 25 April[/td][td]Friday 25 April[/td][td]Saturday 25 April[/td][/tr][tr][td][b]Queen\'s Birthday[/b][/td][td]Monday 10 June[/td][td]Monday 9 June[/td][td]Monday 8 June[/td][/tr][tr][td][b]Melbourne Cup (all of Victoria unless alternate local holiday has been arranged by non-metro council)[/b][/td][td]Tuesday 5 November[/td][td]Tuesday 4 November[/td][td]Tuesday 3 November[/td][/tr][tr][td][b]Christmas Day[/b][/td][td]Wednesday 25 December[/td][td]Thursday 25 December[/td][td]Friday 25 December[/td][/tr][tr][td][b]Boxing Day[/b][/td][td]Thursday 26 December[/td][td]Friday 26 December[/td][td]Saturday 26 December*Monday 28 December *additional day[/td][/tr][/table]','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,221,1365426424,1,'580cc21bb595d9a2a2ab0bca1b2e9859',''),(16,16,0,33,'5 Surprises Cruising Western Australia’s Kimberley Coast',14,221,'Jay',1365427109,'[align=right][img]http://www.petergreenberg.com/wp-content/themes/yamidoo/scripts/timthumb.php?src=http://www.petergreenberg.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/phoca_thumb_l_dsc_5921pr02.jpg&w=310&h=225&zc=1[/img][/align]Largely undeveloped, unpopulated, and one of the least-spoiled marine environments in the world, the Kimberley region is on every Australian’s bucket list but still unheard of to Americans. Thea Klapwald shares five surprises she encountered\r\n\r\nThe Kimberley is known for its remoteness, vast distances, geological antiquity, and tidal variations. It is a land mostly accessible by small aircraft or boat, but I opted for a different, and more relaxing experience.\r\n\r\nI traveled the Kimberley Coast of Western Australia on the Orion cruise for 10 days from the port cities of Broome to Darwin. The Orion is an Australian-owned company founded by Sarina Bratton. Bratton and Friend are proud of the Kimberley itinerary. It is their signature trip and sails from mid-April to mid-September which is the winter, dry season.\r\n\r\nCruising on the Orion, the staff makes the experience. On my voyage, Ship’s Hotel Manager Steve Weber jokingly requested that one guest jump overboard to maintain the one-to-one ratio of crew (76) to guests (77). I knew I really was in for something special when Justin Friend, Orion Expedition Program Manager, started telling me anecdotes about his time on “The Kimberley.” Justin and the crew share a boundless enthusiasm for the region. I was quick to catch Kimberley fever.\r\n\r\n[size=small]Discover Pearls in Broome[/size]\r\n\r\n[url=http://www.petergreenberg.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/800px-Broome_Western_Australia_11.jpg][img=350x250]http://www.petergreenberg.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/800px-Broome_Western_Australia_11.jpg[/img][/url]\r\nBroome is a quaint city to begin any journey. The historic town is the grandfather of the cultivated pearling industry, and is lined with upscale pearl shops and tempting baubles.\r\n\r\nBroome’s Cable Beach stuns you with its unrepentant beauty. Camels, imported over a century ago to combat transportation problems trot politely along the beach for the amusement of tourists.\r\n\r\nOnce the Orion is at sea, leaving Roebuck Harbor and the busyness of Broome behind, what strikes you most along The Kimberley is that no one is there! It is rare to see another ship even in the busy season.\r\n\r\nThe Kimberley is rugged, unsentimental terrain settled by bush adventurers who were considered both hardy and foolhardy.  Its landscape is the backdrop for Baz Luhrman’s operatic film “Australia,” and is as iconic for Australians as the Grand Canyon is for Americans.','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'caadf08d0ba33258c277d07f74c52427',''),(17,17,0,34,'5 ways to go native in Tropical North Queensland',0,221,'Jay',1365428845,'Every year in August, Australia’s culture vultures set their compass due north for Cairns to rub shoulders with 300 of the nation’s leading artists at the [url=http://www.queenslandholidays.com.au/things-to-see-and-do/cairns-indigenous-art-fair-9015900/index.cfm title=cairns indigenous Art Fair]Cairns Indigenous Art Fair[/url]. For some, it’s an opportunity to pick up a bargain from the next big thing. For others, it’s the chance to dive into the Dreamtime with Australia’s first people.\r\n\r\nIf your timing is off kilter for CIAF (this year it’s from August 17–19), don’t sweat. Cairns is the heart of Australia’s best Indigenous experiences. The key is choosing what suits your travel style. Here are five of the best Indigenous experiences:\r\n\r\n[size=medium]1. For Art’s Sake[/size]\r\n\r\n[img]http://bloghub.tq.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/Shelley_KukuYalanji_cropped-567x570.jpg[/img]\r\nCanopy Artspace has to be your first stop. Every day here is an art fair as some of the biggest names in Aboriginal circles like Alick Tipoti pop by to hone – or hang – their latest masterpieces. At the entrance there’s a jaw-droppingly beautiful gallery, but it’s the working studio out back where you can hob nob with the masters. Just don’t expect to see dot art from the desert here. North Queensland artists are influenced by their environment, and the brilliance of the rainforest and reef is their starting point.\r\n[size=medium]\r\n2. Go Walkabout[/size]\r\n\r\nWant to walk in their shoes? Check out some of the best interpretive walks on the planet, but be prepared to go barefoot!\r\n\r\nPart teacher, part preacher, Willie Gordon from Gurrbi Tours makes a whole lot of sense as you tip toe along a magical bush track used by his people for thousands of years. A Nugal-warra elder and master storyteller, Willie has created a half-day adventure that gently probes into the emotions of the group. Don’t be surprised if he asks you if you are a good person (and don’t lie either, I swear this man can see white spots on the tongue). It all makes sense at the sacred Birthing Cave, where ancient ochre rock art portrays a heart-warming story of acceptance and compassion.\r\n\r\nIf you fancy yourself a bit like Bear Grylls and have always wanted to stand ankle deep in mangrove muck with a spear raised high, then Kuku Yalanji Cultural Habitat Tours is for you. Every day, Linc and Brandon Walker invite travellers to go hunting and gathering along the tidal flats of their ancestral country. You have to be prepared to muck in – at times jiving knee deep in mud to dislodge cockles, at others trekking through swampy mangroves to pluck molluscs embedded in muddy roots. But believe me, the little suckers are divine  – you get to eat them later on.\r\n\r\n[size=medium]3. The One-Day Blockbuster[/size]\r\n\r\nIf you’re short on time, need to stick close to Cairns, but still want to pack in the blockbuster experiences, then take a box-office seat at [url=http://www.queenslandholidays.com.au/things-to-see-and-do/tjapukai-aboriginal-cultural-park/index.cfm title=aboriginal culture park in Australia]Tjapukai Aboriginal Cultural Park[/url]. After 25 years of performing for travellers around the globe, this one-stop schmick performance shop has all the key experiences – and with kapow!\r\n[img]http://bloghub.tq.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/Flames_of_the_Forest-638-570x299.jpg[/img]\r\n[size=medium]4. Tuck into Indigenous experiences[/size]\r\n\r\nCombine the five star flavours of bush tucker with a dramatic candle-lit performance atFlames of the Forest. Listed by Australian Traveller as one of the 100 Great Things to do in Australia; dinner under the rainforest canopy comes with a serving of kangaroo and a dash of Indigenous drama.\r\n\r\n[size=medium]5. Say ahh to an Aboriginal Spa[/size]\r\n\r\nIf your idea of a Dreamtime experience is, well, a dream-time experience, then book a 40,000-year-old Aboriginal treatment. Hibiscus Resort & Spa in Port Douglas combines native bush products in its Lit’ya products with kodo – a traditional massage technique that will send your mind on its own walkabout. Be prepared for a few zzzs.','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'a10acd52d7e5fd488996f34d54d83e37',''),(18,18,0,34,'10 best snorkelling sites in Queensland',0,221,'Jay',1365429278,'We’re pretty spoilt here in Queensland with the temperature of the ocean dropping no lower than 21°C during the coldest months of the year and in Tropical North Queensland during the summer months it can hit 28°C – warmer than most baths I’ve taken!\r\n\r\nIf you want to take a closer look into Neptune’s world there are so many idyllic locations to choose from. I’ve managed to single out 10 of the best snorkelling destinations around the islands and beaches of the state that are worth getting wet for!\r\nStraight off the beach…\r\n\r\n\r\n1. Tangalooma Wrecks, Moreton Island\r\n\r\nFifteen wrecks were deliberately sunk just north of Tangalooma Island Resort a few years ago to create a man-made reef, which offers some of the best snorkelling in South East Queensland. Expect to see green turtles, wobbegong sharks, hundreds of fish and maybe even a dugong. Clear water, golden beaches and only an hour from Brisbane.\r\n[img]http://bloghub.tq.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/Wrecks-aerial-photo1-570x427.jpg[/img]\r\n\r\n2. Shelving Beach, Great Keppel Island\r\n\r\nThere’s 17 different beaches on Great Keppel all offering something different from calm swims to roaring surf. On the western tip of the island lies a hidden gem that’s worth exploring – Shelving Beach. It’s accessed from Fisherman’s Beach nestled in between rocky outcrops and coral reefs and there’s always something to see amongst the colourful marine life that lives there.\r\n\r\n3. Chalkies Beach, Haslewood Island, Whitsundays\r\n\r\nWith the world-famous Whitehaven Beach on the opposite shore of Whitsunday Island, Chalkies Beach is often forgotten about. But with its white silica-sand and usually clear waters, the fringing coral reef that lies just offshore adds another reason to stop here, away from the crowds for an underwater adventure with the fishes.\r\n\r\n4. Langford Spit Beach, Whitsundays\r\n\r\n[img]http://bloghub.tq.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/021636-634-570x378.jpg[/img]\r\nTechnically this should be called an island-snorkel but there’s so much beach and so little island it satisfies both categories! It was one of my first-ever snorkels during Best Job in the World and it still sticks in my mind as one of the best.\r\n\r\nLangford Island has a huge variety of soft and hard corals in every shape, size and colour can be found here. In 45 minutes I managed to photograph all of these with a simple underwater compact camera. Truly memorable.\r\n\r\n[img]http://farm3.staticflickr.com/2573/3739504490_9fd7b3c8dd.jpg[/img]\r\n5. Geoffrey Bay Snorkel Trail – Magnetic Island\r\n\r\nBefore starting out make sure you collect a swim-card from one of the retailers on the island then wander straight off the beach opposite Arcadia Hotel and follow the surface and sub-surface floats that have been installed there for a fantastic guided tour of Geoffrey Bay.\r\n\r\nThere are loads of fish around the wreck of the Moltke and stronger swimmers can continue on to the WWII aeroplane propeller and engine block from a CW-22B Curtiss Falcon. Magnetic Island is full of old military surprises above, and below the water.\r\n\r\nDownload a PDF for a map of the trails here - Magnetic Island Snorkel Trail Info\r\nIsland secrets…\r\n\r\n[img]http://www.queenslandholidays.com.au/things-to-see-and-do/langford-island/index.cfm[/img]\r\n6. Lady Elliot Island, Southern Great Barrier Reef\r\n\r\nAs the tide drops away the lagoon out the front of the restaurant on Lady Elliot Island comes into its own, with deep channels left between the coral reef flats that concentrate the marine life into easy-to-swim-through pools and gullies. If you’re a nervous swimmer or Olympic hopeful there’s something to keep you amused as you wind your way over sea cucumbers, past turtles and out into the open ocean.\r\n\r\n[img]http://bloghub.tq.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/DSC_0256-638-570x388.jpg[/img]\r\n7. Hayman Island, Whitsundays\r\n\r\nBlue Pearl Bay on the northern side of the island is a little piece of paradise. Hundreds of people visit here every year and there’s a simple reason – impeccable fringing coral reef.\r\n\r\nI don’t think there are many other places on the planet where you can rub noses with friendly Maori wrasse, swim through soft coral gardens, be surrounded by hundreds of reef fish all off the beach or the back of your tour boat. Make sure you have an empty memory card as you’ll be snapping continually at this site!\r\n\r\n8. Orpheus Island, north of Townsville\r\n\r\nThe world-class snorkel site outside the Research Station on Orpheus Island to the north of the main resort is somewhere I could spend days. Not only are there hundreds of giant clams (which have to be seen squirting water at low tide – see the video below), some of the most colourful colour bommies on the entire Great Barrier Reef, thousands of damsel fish but also sheltered warm waters in the lee of the island.\r\n\r\nNo wonder James Cook University have their students out here to study marine science!\r\n\r\n9. Green Island, off Cairns\r\n\r\nWith seagrass beds to the west and coral reef to the east, Green Island has to be one of the easiest ways to introduce yourself to snorkelling if you’re a first time water baby.\r\n\r\nTurtles are in abundance, as are stingrays, reef fish and you may even spot a migrating humpback whale cruise past the island between June and October.\r\n\r\n10. Low Isles, off Port Douglas\r\n\r\nWith spectacular coral reef surrounding the picturesque Low Isles this is probably my most complete snorkel site of the lot. The range of hard corals is huge with colourful staghorn, plate and brain coral bommies creating an undulating sea floor which reef sharks, turtles and rays all call home.\r\n\r\nI struggle to pull myself away and am always the last one to hop back in the boat every time I visit. Make sure you have your mask cleared and your camera fully charged – oh the memories are flooding back!\r\n[img]http://bloghub.tq.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/014216-634-2-570x380.jpg[/img]\r\n\r\nWherever you decide to dive into the water you’re bound to come up at the end fulfilled and exhilarated. Just remember to always snorkel with a buddy, apply loads of sunscreen well before entering the water and please don’t touch or handle anything below the surface – we are mere visitors in the marine world!\r\n\r\nHave a superb time underwater.\r\n\r\nBen:D','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'4cd05dfcbfc1badc9288e99181812c32',''),(19,19,0,35,'Adelaide and South Australia',0,221,'Jay',1365429436,'http://youtu.be/FoBxq8lB2iY\n\nAdelaide is a city of great visual harmony and classical elegant style, superbly set beside the River Torrens between the Adelaide Hills and waters of Gulf St Vincent.\n\nThe wine and festival capital of Australia, Adelaide is a place to experience the buzz, culture and convenience of a big city without the frustrations. The city centre, surrounded by parklands, is a charming blend of historic buildings, wide streets, groovy shops, street cafes and restaurants. And because Adelaide is known as the 20-minute city, you can experience it all on a series of easy short walks.','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,221,1365429513,1,'3fe4ae3f99d3458b38d089b40840ffa3',''),(20,20,0,35,'Life in Adelaide - 1966',0,221,'Jay',1365429539,'Http://youtu.be/RkNeNF2-Esw','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'836aaac55b35f9fc9346f0ee9a59784a',''),(21,21,0,17,'A Student\'s Day in Brisbane',0,221,'Jay',1365429744,'Http://youtu.be/NrR2XqCGBWA\r\n\r\n[b]baliko2007[/b]\r\n\r\nI used to be an int. student in Brisbane and this commercial does not reflect students\' real daily life.If you wealthy enough, then yes, you can enjoy such \'lavish\' student life style with living in the city, do all sorts of fun hobbies, travelling, fine dining etc. But this is not how the average international student lives in Brisbane. It\'s too far fetched and superficial...\r\n\r\n[b]bristv[/b]\r\n\r\nThanks for your comment. You will be surprised to know that the majority of the activities in the film are free of charge or educational experiences that you receive from studying in Brisbane. For more ideas of free things to do in Brisbane take a look at the \"Fun for Free\" page on the Visit Brisbane website.','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'f03fdf5b34fbf3edd42582692d0b6e0d',''),(22,22,0,17,'Australian universities improve world standing',0,221,'Jay',1365429776,'AUSTRALIAN universities have improved their international standing in the past year and now enjoy the third highest ranked reputation in the world.\r\n\r\nThe Times Higher Education World Reputation Rankings, to be released today, found Australian now lags only behind the US and UK, with six of our universities ranked in the Top 100.\r\n\r\nIn the past year, Australian universities outperformed the Netherlands, Japan and Germany, with two new entrants on the list _ Monash University in Victoria, and the University of NSW _ joining the four existing place holders.\r\n\r\nThe University of Melbourne improved its rank from 43 to 39 and Australian National University from 44 to 42. Sydney University rose one place to 49, and University of Queensland remained in the 80th percentile.\r\n\r\nTimes Higher Education editor Phil Baty said the reputation rankings have been held since 2011 and Australia has improved its standing at each survey.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe results are based on a global opinion poll and take into account more than 16,000 responses from senior published academics in 150 countries.\r\n\r\n\"Australia is a country very much on the way up in terms of worldwide academic prestige,\" Mr Baty said in a statement.\r\n\r\n\"In many ways these results show that Australia\'s image among scholars around the world is catching up with the reality: until now it has tended to perform less well in the reputation rankings compared with the overall, objective World University Rankings.\r\n\r\n\"These results show how well poised Australia is to make the most of its geographical advantages: while it has strong links with the best universities in the West, it has also made the most of East Asia\'s booming higher education scene. If it continues to exploit these opportunities, Australia could be a serious beneficiary of the Asian century, which is great news for its economy and competitiveness.\"\r\n\r\nMonash University president Ed Byrne said in a statement: \"Australia is ideally situation between the rising academic powerhouses of Asia and established centres in the old Westticipate a bright future.\"\r\n\r\nUNSW Vice Chancellor, Professor Fred Hilmer, put the institution\'s first-time inclusion down to a \"very strong improvement path\".\r\n\r\n\"When you look at the quality of the student intake, it\'s gone up every year. It\'s harder and harder to get in and if you look at research in particular, we are winning increasingly competitive grants,\" Professor Hilmer said.\r\n\r\nUniversities in the US and UK still hold the bulk of the top 100 positions, (43 in the US and nine in the UK) with an elite group of six \"super-brands\" including Harvard, Oxford and Cambridge, holding the top positions since the rankings\' inception.\r\n\r\nThe highest ranking university outside of the US and UK is the University of Tokyo at 9th, while India and New Zealand are among the countries with no entrants on the Top 100 list. China\'s two most prestigious universities, Tsinghua University and Peking University, both dropped slightly in the rankings, but they remain in the Top 50.\r\n\r\nSource: HeraldSun http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/australian-universities-improve-world-standing/story-e6frf7kx-1226590402495','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'0c7d632ba63c1f8c195c36d72eea6dcd',''),(23,23,0,17,'New post-study work arrangements and international students',0,221,'Jay',1365429863,'New post-study work arrangements are being introduced in early 2013 for eligible international students who graduate with an Australian Bachelor’s, Master’s or a Doctoral degree.\r\n\r\nThe new post-study work arrangements will be built as an additional stream in the existing temporary skilled graduate (subclass 485) visa. The subclass 485 currently allows international students who graduate with skills and qualifications that relate to an occupation that is in demand to remain in Australia for an additional 18 months.\r\n\r\nFrom early 2013, the temporary skilled graduate (subclass 485) visa will be renamed the temporary graduate (subclass 485) visa. You may apply for the temporary graduate visa through either the new post-study work stream (the new arrangements) or the graduate work stream (the existing subclass 485 arrangements) provided you meet the specific eligibility requirements.\r\n\r\nThe post-study work stream of the subclass 485 will be for international students who lodged their first student visa application after the introduction of the genuine temporary entrant requirement (GTE) on 5 November 2011. If you do not meet this requirement, you may still be eligible for a temporary graduate visa through the graduate work stream.\r\n\r\nThe introduction of new post-study work arrangements for degree level graduates in Australia was a key recommendation of the Strategic review of the student visa program 2011, conducted by the Hon Michael Knight AO.\r\n\r\nWe have recently published updated information on our website with details about how the new arrangements will work and what the particular eligibility requirements will be. You can view this information here.\r\n\r\nMore important information about the new post-study work stream of the subclass 485:\r\nEligible qualifications\r\n\r\n\r\nTo be eligible for the new post-study work arrangements, you must graduate from an Australian educational institution with a Bachelor’s, Master’s and/or Doctoral degree. You may qualify for the new arrangements using any combination of eligible degree level qualifications.\r\n\r\nThe study used to complete this qualification must have been at Bachelor level and above and must meet the Australian study requirement.\r\nThe Australian study requirement\r\n\r\n\r\nRegardless of whether you are applying under the new post-study work stream or the graduate work stream, you must meet the Australian study requirement in the six months before making your subclass 485 application. The Australian study requirement is defined as study in Australia in a registered course for a period of at least two academic years. The course must be conducted in English and must be completed in no less than 16 calendar months.\r\n\r\nWe have developed a fact sheet with information on how the Australian study requirement is assessed for the purposes of applying for a temporary graduate visa.  This new fact sheet can be found here.\r\n\r\nAre the new arrangements linked to skilled migration?\r\n\r\nThe new arrangements are not linked to skilled migration and do not provide a pathway to permanent residence. Therefore applicants under the new post-study work stream will not be required to nominate a skilled occupation or submit a skills assessment. Applicants under the graduate work stream of the subclass 485 will still be required to nominate a skilled occupation and submit a suitable skills assessment.\r\n\r\nIt is important to note that student visas and the graduate work visa are temporary visas and there is no guarantee that, on the basis of having held one of these visas, you will meet the requirements for grant of another visa.\r\nVisa validity\r\n\r\n\r\nUnder the new post-study work arrangements, the duration of the subclass 485 visa you are granted will depend on the qualification that you have used to qualify for the arrangements.\r\n\r\nGraduates who have completed a Bachelor’s degree, Master’s by coursework degree or Master’s extended degree may be eligible to apply for a two year post-study work visa. Graduates who have completed a Master’s by research degree or a Doctorate may be eligible to apply for a three or four year post-study work visa respectively.\r\n\r\nOther graduates may be eligible to apply for an 18 month subclass 485 visa through the graduate work stream.\r\n\r\nSource: The Migration Blog','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'2cb037e6596d53ed827d3b0d7bf2d914',''),(24,24,0,18,'Butcher Salary Australia',0,221,'Jay',1365430365,'Salaries are per year unless otherwise specified (eg: /hour).\r\n\r\nThe ANZSCO (The Australian and New Zealand Standard Classification of Occupations) code for butchers is 351211.\r\n\r\nJob titles and exact tasks vary in this work and examples of some occupation titles are butcher, retail butcher, qualified butcher, head butcher and apprentice butcher.\r\n\r\nIn 2010, the food industry has given to workers an average salary of $854/week in ordinary earnings. The average earnings rising to $890/week for those who do overtime and worked an average of 39.5 hours a week.1\r\nButcher Salaries / Wages in 2011 – 2012\r\n\r\n[table=35][tr][td][b]Job title[/b][/td][td][b]wage/salary  $[/b][/td][td][b]Location[/b][/td][/tr][tr][td]Qualified Butcher[/td][td]20 – 25 per hour[/td][td]Sydney[/td][/tr][tr][td]Apprentice Butcher[/td][td]10 – 20 per hour[/td][td]Sydney[/td][/tr][tr][td]Qualified Head Butcher[/td][td]20 – 25 per hour[/td][td]Melbourne[/td][/tr][tr][td]Butcher – Gourmet[/td][td]20 – 30 per hour[/td][td]Brisbane[/td][/tr][tr][td]Qualified Butcher / 2IC[/td][td]50,000 – 65,000[/td][td]Queensland[/td][/tr][tr][td]Qualified Butcher[/td][td]35,000 – 45,000[/td][td]Queensland[/td][/tr][tr][td]Apprentice Butcher[/td][td]15,000 – 25,000[/td][td]Perth[/td][/tr][tr][td]Qualified Butcher[/td][td]40,000 – 45,000[/td][td]Perth[/td][/tr][/table]\r\n\r\nThe data has been taken from ABS (Australian Bureau of Statistics)','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'35e10781bb7044612ee5299c22cf4ca7',''),(25,25,0,18,'5 Reasons to Become an Electrician',0,221,'Jay',1365430495,'Choosing a career that embodies all the important aspects for a long career can be a difficult choice. However, despite the current jobs climate and unemployment levels, there are several industries that are surviving with demand remaining constant for their services. One such example of these industries is electricians.\r\n\r\nElectricians make solid salaries and with their skills always in demand for installation, maintenance and repair work on a multitude of electrical projects. Being an electrician offers jobs security, decent benefits, and quality wages. Below you will find five of the best reasons why people move into the field of electricians and the long term benefits.\r\n\r\n1. Salary\r\n\r\nOne of the most attractive aspects of the job and reason why many people get into the field of electrician is the potential high salary earnings. An electrician\'s salary is determined by several factors including the type of job, number of years in the job, and the level of licence held. Self-employed electrician salaries can potentially be much higher than those who work for a company due to the fact that there is the removal of overhead and benefits. However, self-employed workers have to cover their own benefits.\r\n\r\nThe electrician salary will vary depending on where the electrician is based, are self employed and what kinds of projects they take on.\r\n\r\nStarting salaries for qualified electricians are between $32,000 and $35,000, with more experienced electricians sometimes earning up to $80,000 per year. This is also dependent on the individual electricians qualifications, for example electrician salaries for those trained to install or repair elevators will earn anywhere from $39,500 to $86,000 per year.\r\n\r\n2. Electricians are Careers, not just Jobs\r\n\r\n\"The electrical industry is experiencing rapid technological change, and therefore requires entrants to this field to have the ability to meet the demands of this flexible, challenging and life-long rewarding career. Positions and opportunities range from trade level through to middle management, engineering roles and business ownership,\" according to an Electrical Contractors Association spokesperson.\r\n\r\nChoosing a career as an electrician opens a range of career and specialty options with choices between being self-employed or as part of a larger business. What\'s more, within the electrical industry many electricians\' select a specialty that they focus on whether it is manufacturing, mining, building and construction, energy or water supply industries with jobs being even more focused within these various sectors\r\n\r\n3. Electrician Skills Shortage\r\n\r\nDue to the increasing skills shortage that is emerging in the electrician industry, there is a great deal of interest as people are looking for jobs security in the face of an uncertain Australian jobs market. Becoming an electrician offers a lifelong career as the need for electricians cannot dissipate while electrical systems need to be installed and maintained by professional, on both a residential and commercial front.\r\n\r\n4. Mentally and Physically Challenging\r\n\r\nElectricians are able to take on various different jobs and projects, ranging from major commercial projects in large cities to various small residential wiring jobs. Being an electrician offers mental skills such as interpreting electrical or electronic drawings and determining wiring layouts in addition to the obvious physical skills including use of various sophisticated equipment and electrical projects.\r\n\r\n5. Changing \'Office\'\r\n\r\nBeing an electrician allows for a diverse and changing work environment with various individual jobs being part of many electrician average working weeks. Your average electrician can easily move from outdoor projects such as supply cables and street lighting to indoor projects including buildings under construction or residential projects. This diversity can differ depending on the jobs focus of the electrician with electrical jobs arising anywhere from commercial, housing, industrial and mining sectors.\r\n\r\nSource - electrician.com.au http://www.electrician.com.au/articles/5-reasons-to-become-an-electrician/','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'eae347c67e291e74e62e0a7b0e3183e2',''),(26,26,0,18,'Which IT Pro Roles Pay The Best ?',0,221,'Jay',1365431437,'It’s the question every IT worker asks: which specialisation should I choose to maximise my earning potential? Right now, if you’re looking for a lucrative job, enterprise architecture and cloud computing top the bill. Check out these salary tables for more insights.\r\n\r\nThe ICT Salary & Employment Insight report from Hudson provides some insights into growth areas for IT salaries. The study is based on a survey of 1025 employees and 823 employers across Australia.\r\n\r\nMoney is only one part of employment satisfaction, but we shouldn’t kid ourselves that it’s irrelevant. When asked what factors would influence their choice of the next job, more pay was the top response (both for IT workers and for other employment categories Hudson covered). More than half (56.7 per cent) were looking for a new role.\r\n\r\nThat doesn’t mean a pay rise will be forthcoming. Hudson’s research suggests that 65.1 per cent of employees plan increases of between 2 to 3 per cent this year. However, IT workers have done better in this area in the past than other sectors, with 91.7 per cent offering an increase over the last 12 months.\r\n\r\n“In the permanent market there have been very conservative hiring practices,” Hudson client services director Martin Retschko told Lifehacker. “People are working harder and there’s less replacement going on. Organisations are having to do more with less. The overriding trend is that people are feeling the pressure.”\r\n\r\nOne potential strategy for employers is to work on more flexible workplace practices, such as offering more personal days or flexible hours. However, that’s a relatively rare option, according to Retschko. “Offering the ability to work from home or taking personal days — those things are very valuable, but a lot of organisations are still very traditional.”\r\n\r\nAs ever, salaries vary depending on where you’re located. This is often a two-edged sword; getting paid more in Perth doesn’t help if rents are going through the roof. We’re looking here at a selection of permanent roles (Hudson also 