Architect[/td][td]120-150[/td][td]120-150[/td][td]100-150[/td][td]100-150[/td][td]100-150[/td][td]100-120[/td][td]100-150[/td][/tr][tr][td]Data Centre Manager[/td][td]100-140[/td][td]120-140[/td][td]90-130[/td][td]100-150[/td][td]80-120[/td][td]110-130[/td][td]100-125[/td][/tr][tr][td]Security Administrator[/td][td]80-110[/td][td]85-110[/td][td]70-95[/td][td]65-95[/td][td]75-90[/td][td]80-100[/td][td]60-90[/td][/tr][tr][td]IT Manager[/td][td]100-170[/td][td]90-150[/td][td]100-170[/td][td]100-150[/td][td]90-150[/td][td]90-150[/td][td]90-150[/td][/tr][tr][td]CIO[/td][td]180-370[/td][td]180-250[/td][td]170-350[/td][td]150-250[/td][td]180-300[/td][td]150-300[/td][td]170+[/td][/tr][/table]\r\n\r\nWhile technical skills are a pre-requisite for many of these jobs, you also need to work on other areas. “Soft skills around relationship management space are very important,” said Retschko.','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'b4bec5ef01c9f762e6065fade2b9424a',''),(27,27,0,19,'Perth to lead house price growth over next three years, with Sydney and Brisbane also',0,221,'Jay',1365432070,'Perth house prices are expected to grow by a cumulative 20.4% over the next three years to 2015, according to the latest QBE LMI Housing Outlook report prepared by BIS Shrapnel.\n\nThe report anticipates the median Perth house price to rise from $505,000 to $580,000 over the next three years, with strong growth also expected for Brisbane (from $450,000 to $515,000) and Sydney ($660,000 to $750,000).\n\nSydney house price growth is expected to be modest in 2013, at just 2.7%, but is forecast to pick up in 2014 and 2015.\n\nDarwin house prices are also expected to continue to surge rising to a median of $650,000 – making it the second most expensive housing market after Sydney.\n\nMelbourne house prices will continue to tread water over the next three years, rising by less than 2% annually to 2015, with median house price increasing from $540,000 to $557,000, according to the report.\n\nModest house price growth is also anticipated for Adelaide, Canberra and Hobart.\n\n Median house price growth forecasts 2013 – 2015 (major capitals)\n[table=40][tr][td][/td][td]Perth[/td][td]Brisbane[/td][td]Sydney[/td][td]Adelaide[/td][td]Melbourne[/td][/tr][tr][td]2013[/td][td]6.3%[/td][td]3.9%[/td][td]2.7%[/td][td]1.3%[/td][td]0.9%[/td][/tr][tr][td]2014[/td][td]7.9%[/td][td]7.8%[/td][td]6.1%[/td][td]2.5%[/td][td]1.5%[/td][/tr][tr][td]2015[/td][td]6.2%[/td][td]6.2%[/td][td]7.1%[/td][td]2.4%[/td][td]1.6%[/td][/tr][tr][td]2015 Median[/td][td]$580,000[/td][td]$515,000[/td][td]$750,000[/td][td]$580,000[/td][td]$557,000[/td][/tr][/table]\n\nMedian house price growth forecasts 2013 – 2015 (minor capitals)\n[table=40][tr][td][/td][td]Darwin[/td][td]Canberra[/td][td]Hbart[/td][/tr][tr][td]2013[/td][td]5.3%[/td][td]-0.8%[/td][td]-1.1%[/td][/tr][tr][td]2014[/td][td]5%[/td][td]0%[/td][td]1.1%[/td][/tr][tr][td]2015[/td][td]3.2%[/td][td]1.4%[/td][td]1.4%[/td][/tr][tr][td]2015 Median[/td][td]$650,000[/td][td]$498,000[/td][td]$375,000[/td][/tr][/table]\n\nSource: BIS Shrapnel\n\nThe report says the residential market in Perth has stagnated after prices peaked in December 2007, with the median house price reaching $478,000 as a result of deteriorating housing affordability.\n\n“Conditions in Perth are now beginning to turn around and point to a recovery.\n\n“The combination of rising underlying demand and falling completions has seen a substantial deficiency emerge.\n\n“This is being reflected in vacancy rates falling to 1.9% in June 2012, which is well below the balanced market rate of 3%, and underpinning stronger rental growth.\"\n\nThe report also notes that employment growth has also been strong, with the unemployment rate well below 5% while affordability has also improved significantly.”\n\nIn addition, “rising investment in new mining and resource projects will lead to further improvement in sentiment”.\n\nThe relatively strong outlook for Sydney is based on rental growth continuing to remain solid, “outpacing recent price growth, and driving an improvement in yields”.\n\n“First-home buyer demand — albeit inconsistent due to changes in state government first home buyer incentives — appears to be improving, while the extended period of weak prices together with interest rate reductions over 2011-12 mean that affordability is now at its best level since 2001.\n\n“Given this, the main factor holding back the Sydney market now appears to be confidence. With economic growth forecast to become more broad based outside the resource sector in 2012-13, this should help sentiment,” says the report.\n\nHowever, in Melbourne “high level of new dwelling construction has coincided with slowing population growth and the market is estimated to have moved from close to balance at June 2011, to a rising underlying surplus of dwellings at June 2012”.\n\nAs a result rental vacancy rates have also begun to increase and are expected to continue to rise as most of the investor-purchased apartments work their way through to completion.\n\nThe report says there is little in the Melbourne market at the moment to drive demand or price growth, but major price declines are not expected.\n\nLooking at the housing market as a whole, Jenny Boddington, chief executive of QBE LMI, says the affordability of housing is “currently at its best level across most capital cities since the first half of last decade, with the exception of a brief period in 2009 when affordability spiked due to aggressive cuts in interest rates”.\n\n“Notably, affordability is expected to further improve as standard variable interest rates are tipped to fall by another 25 basis points in 2012-13.\n\n“Consequently, we should see increased housing turnover in the market as first home buyer numbers pick up and have a positive effect on upgrader activity, which in turn is predicted to further spur investors return to the market.”\n\nThe report also says first-home buyer demand is now trending upwards following depressed activity since 2008-09.','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,221,1365432108,1,'812abecf182b75ca00c9e9c8c3b0b414',''),(28,28,0,20,'Myth Busters: 5 truths about sharks',0,221,'Jay',1365432866,'Sharks: They’re not the prettiest fish in the sea, but they’re also not as scary as you might think! Most divers rejoice in spotting one while some swimmers won’t dare to go more than ankle-deep in the surf for fear of attack.\r\n\r\nBut whichever way you look at it, sharks are a really important part of the marine eco-system. Without them, other species can over-populate reefs resulting in a total breakdown of the natural feeding hierarchy.\r\n\r\nWe decided to break down five common shark tales to sort the fact from the fiction.\r\n\r\n\r\nMyth #1: Sharks have humans on the menu.\r\n\r\nFact: Sharks hunt using their sensory systems not their eyesight (which is pretty terrible). They’ll often hunt in river-mouths, murky water and at sunrise or sunset and will bump their prey before attacking it.\r\n\r\nTo a shark, a surfer can look just like a seal from below – one of the favourite snacks of larger, temperate water shark species.\r\n\r\nMyth #2: Any shark is a bad shark.\r\n\r\nFact: Around the world there are over 500 species of sharks, some tiny, like the Dwarf Lantern Shark at 19 centimeters long, to the Whale Shark at over 15 metres in length.\r\n\r\nSome live at the very bottom of the ocean and some are surface feeders, but almost all will swim away from you when approached.\r\n\r\nOn the Great Barrier Reef there are eight different species of sharks, and only two of these have ever been known to attack humans. There is an infinitesimally small chance of ever seeing one, let alone it threatening you!\r\n\r\nMyth #3: Sharks are man-eaters, full-stop.\r\n\r\nFact: Not every shark eats large prey. Whitetip, Blacktip and Lemon Sharks, most commonly found on the Great Barrier Reef, survive on small fish no bigger than your hand. They’re easy to catch and you’ll often see them hunting in the shallow waters around the reefs where they can be easily cornered.\r\n\r\nWhale Sharks are becoming more common in the Coral Sea, and these huge beasts survive on plankton alone!\r\n\r\nMyth #4: Sharks will die if they stop swimming.\r\n\r\n\r\nFact: Sharks propel themselves forward to breathe, well most of them anyway. But there are some, like Leopard Sharks, who have the ability to pump water through their body and over their gills whilst they rest on the sea bed.\r\n\r\nSwimming through the water provides the best way for a shark to breathe but they can relax and take in the view too!\r\n\r\nMyth #5: Shark fins will boost sexual potency, enhance skin quality, increase one’s Qi or energy, prevent heart disease, and lower cholesterol.\r\nFact: Much like rhino horn, bear bile and tiger claws there are no proven medicinal benefits to consuming shark fin. They taste of very little, being pure gristle and sinew and they’re not going to improve your sex-life either!\r\n\r\nShark finning is a major worldwide problem with ten of millions being killed every year to supply the lucrative Asian food industry. They’re often caught, have their fins sliced off and are thrown back into the water alive, with the fisherman keeping only what he needs.\r\n\r\nThe Great Barrier Reef Marine Park offers a high level of protection for all shark species. It’s broken up into zones that safe-guard breeding grounds and nursery areas for many species resulting in a healthy population of all sharks on the reef.\r\n\r\nThe vast majority of tourism operators help the Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority (GBRMPA) with a monitoring program called ‘Eye on the Reef’. Sightings of iconic species are recorded every time they are witnessed and sent to GBRMPA, giving a valuable insight into what happens with shark populations along the length of this World Heritage Site.','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'e26d37b8ab6c398cc9e2d4e26025bad5',''),(29,29,0,21,'UV radiation in Australia',0,221,'Jay',1365433429,'Australians take very seriously the UV radiation. Oz has the highest rate of skin cancer in the world and it\'s no wonder, just look at the pictures below.\n[size=medium]\nWhat is UV radiation ?[/size]\n\nWell, i could give you a definition but it\'s boring and you can read that on Wikipedia anyway. Long story short, the Sun emits some types of radiation - visible light, infrared radiation (which u feel as heat) and UV radiation which u cannot see nor feel.\n\nPeople in general mistake the UV radiation with the infrared radiation. When the temperature is low it means that there are fewer infrared radiation but that does not mean that the UV radiation are low.\n\n[size=medium]Types of UV radiation[/size]\n\nUV radiation are categorized after theyr wavelength: UVA, UVB and UVC\n[list][*]UV-A reaches the Earth from the sun in the greatest quantities. Recent information suggests that UV-A can damage the skins immune system. UV-A from the sun passes right through the ozone layer to the Earths surface with little attenuation\n[*]UV-B radiation is potentially very harmful. Fortunately, most of the sun\'s UV-B radiation is absorbed by ozone in the stratosphere.\n[*]UV-C radiation is potentially the most damaging because it is very energetic. Fortunately, all UV-C is absorbed by oxygen and ozone in the stratosphere and never reaches the Earth\'s surface.\n[/list]\n[size=medium]Factors that affect the amount of UV radiation[/size]\n\nThe amount of UV radiation is different through the day, every day of every month in every season of every year.\nThe total amount of UV radiation in one place will be affected by:\n[list][*]proximity to the Ecuador\n[*]time of day\n[*]day of the year\n[*]amount of clouds\n[*]altitude\n[*]reflection[/list]\n\nTable of UV reflectances\n\nSurface	Reflectance........................................... (%)\nSnow (new)........................................................88\nSnow (old)..........................................................50\nSea surf (white foam)......................................25 to 30\nSand (dry)..........................................................18\nSand (wet)..........................................................7\nConcrete footpath.............................................8 to 12\nBoat deck (wood to fibreglass)...........................6 to 9\nOpen water or ocean........................................3 to 8\nSoil.................................................................4 to 6\nLawn grass......................................................2 to 5\n[b]\nMedian UV radiation - Annually[/b]\n\n[img]http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/map/uv-index/uv-an.png[/img]\n\n[b]January[/b]\n\n[img]http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/map/uv-index/uv-jan.png[/img]\n\n[b]February[/b]\n\n[img]http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/map/uv-index/uv-feb.png[/img]\n\n[b]March[/b]\n\n[img]http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/map/uv-index/uv-mar.png[/img]\n\n[b]April[/b]\n\n[img]http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/map/uv-index/uv-apr.png[/img]\n\n[b]Mai[/b]\n\n[img]http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/map/uv-index/uv-may.png[/img]\n\n[b]June[/b]\n\n[img]http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/map/uv-index/uv-jun.png[/img]\n\n[b]July[/b]\n\n[img]http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/map/uv-index/uv-jul.png[/img]\n\n[b]August[/b]\n\n[img]http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/map/uv-index/uv-aug.png[/img]\n\n[b]September[/b]\n\n[img]http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/map/uv-index/uv-sep.png[/img]','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,221,1365433473,1,'a85f4ab931cb9fbf7fb48b31b0f314e9',''),(31,29,29,21,'RE: UV radiation in Australia',0,221,'Jay',1365435563,'[b]October[/b]\r\n\r\n[img]http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/map/uv-index/uv-oct.png[/img]\r\n\r\n[b]November[/b]\r\n\r\n[img]http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/map/uv-index/uv-nov.png[/img]\r\n\r\n[b]December[/b]\r\n\r\n[img]http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/map/uv-index/uv-dec.png[/img]','108.162.249.42',1822619946,0,0,0,0,1,'a84edf6f7326c1b555a207a230f0136d',''),(42,31,0,23,'Amazing sunset in Sydney',0,221,'Jay',1365470444,'[img]http://sphotos-h.ak.fbcdn.net/hphotos-ak-snc6/270713_10151507322515909_1914188141_n.jpg[/img]','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'2f29f2187ed4c21645b86b56e425e112',''),(43,32,0,23,'Ocean pools in NSW',0,221,'Jay',1365470487,'[img]http://www.beozzie.com/sites/default/files/856971_537961426226873_59118186_o%20(2).jpg[/img]','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'ead94c6a9167fe1c62a698b94d98642d',''),(44,33,0,23,'The koala',0,221,'Jay',1365470541,'The koala is found in coastal regions of eastern and southern Australia, from Adelaide to the southern part of Cape York Peninsula. Populations also extend for considerable distances inland in regions with enough moisture to support suitable woodlands. The koalas of South Australia were largely exterminated during the early part of the 20th century, but the state has since been repopulated with Victorian stock. The koala is not found in Tasmania, the Northern Territory or Western Australia. As of 2012 there have been increasing concerns about the animal\'s sustainable future in the environment.\r\n\r\nThe koala sleeps about 18 hours every day to conserve energy as the Eucalypt leaves is low on nutriements.\r\n\r\n[img]http://www.beozzie.com/sites/default/files/koala.JPG[/img]','58.6.253.235',973536747,0,0,0,0,1,'d6a22329b0622ce40a6685934124816e',''),(45,34,0,19,'Perth and Darwin Rental Prices Hitting Record Levels',0,221,'Jay',1365815223,'It’s been a little while since we wrote an article about the cost of housing in Australia so thought it might be a good time to see what’s going on!.\r\n\r\nHaving done a little research on the matter, it would seem that for some new arrivals to Australia, it’s not all good news.\r\n\r\nFor those looking to move to Western Australia or the Northern territory, it’s worth noting that renting a home in Perth is now nearly as expensive as Sydney, with the mining boom driving rents to a record level. Fresh figures from the Real Estate Institute Of Western Australia (REIWA) show that in the three months to February metropolitan rents in Perth increased by 4.4 per cent, lifting the overall median from $450 to $490 per week, and representing a rise of $60 on the same time last year.\r\n\r\nThe research shows a house now costs $490 a week to rent in Perth and $700 a week in Darwin. Meanwhile, rental growth has been non-existent in Sydney and Melbourne for more than a year.\r\n\r\nIt’s all down to the highly paid fly-in fly-out workers apparently who can afford to bid up the price of housing well beyond the levels that locals could afford. Perth house rents rose 22.5 per cent and units by 17.1 per cent in the last year. The vacancy rate for rental properties was just 0.9 per cent in February, according to research by a company called SQM.\r\n\r\n[img]http://i.imgur.com/FGPbo7T.png[/img]\r\nHow rent prices have moved\r\n\r\nResearch has also found that costs are even steeper in Darwin, where a much smaller population and supply of housing stock is struggling to contend with an influx of workers for the liquid national gas projects. In the last year, Darwin house rents soared 22.8 per cent and unit rents by 22.2 per cent. Only 1.3 per cent of rental properties are currently available there.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, rents for houses in Melbourne held at $360 and have not experienced any growth in more than two years. Unit rents rose just 1.4 per cent, well below the rate of inflation.\r\n\r\nIn Sydney, house rents held steady at $500 for the year, but unit rents have risen by 4.4 per cent. About 2.7 per cent of rental properties are vacant in Melbourne and 1.5 per cent in Sydney, A much better position for those looking to move to the south and east coasts.\r\n\r\nSo there we have it. How will this effect where you’re wanting to settle if at all?','58.6.249.164',973535652,0,0,0,0,1,'b20a779564913a397db42c6d7bb88498',''),(46,35,0,16,'Money required to move (relocation) in Australia',0,222,'Pops',1365937299,'I am often asked a lot of weird questions about Australia and our relocation there. To my surprise, not many are asking how much money you need to move to Australia and to live there (at least untill you find a job).\r\n\r\n[size=medium]So... how much money you need in Australia ?[/size]\r\nEven with a lot of informations it is hard to do an estimate but when someone asks you the following question: \"We are 2 and have 2 babies and we would like to know how much will we need to move to Aus and to have a decent life ?\" you can\'t just ignore this.\r\n\r\nYou need to take into account a lot of things before you can make an estimate for a comfortable living for you and your family. You should write down the following spendings:\r\n[list]\r\n[*]rent or mortgage\r\n[*]car maintenance\r\n[*]food costs\r\n[*]utilities: electricity, gas, water\r\n[*]usual stuff: clothes, jewels, computer, toys, etc\r\n[*]health insurance and home insurance\r\n[*]telephone related costs - prepaid or postpaid plans\r\n[*]unexpected costs\r\n[list][*]car repairs\r\n[*]home repairs\r\n[*]broken stuff around the house\r\n[*]other things arround the house/car/etc\r\n[/list][/list]\r\n\r\nYou need to answer those sort of questions and you can make an estimate. It\'s pretty hard for me to answer these questions for you but i can lay down some general costs.\r\n\r\n[list]\r\n[*]Gas - $100\r\n[*]water - $70 - 100\r\n[*]electricity - $75 - 100\r\n[*]food for 2 - $1000\r\n[*]rent - $1500 - $2500\r\n[*]electronics - about the same as in Europe. Though Apple is a 50% more here\r\n[*]cars - expensive, EU models are verry expensive (esp. parts)\r\n[*]clothes - for all tastes, cheap and expensive\r\n[*]prepaid phones - $40 unlimited phone calls and between 2 and 4 GB of data\r\n[*]internet - between $40 and $100\r\n[*]smokes - $12 - $15/pack\r\n[/list]\r\n\r\nI gaved you some prices from Melbourne. Other cities may have lower or higher prices for those exact tings esp for rent, electricity and utilities. The rent can vary greatly between suburbs so ... \r\n\r\nA simpler solution for those who come from UK: Double your spendings from UK and you should find out how much money you will need here for the same lifestyle. If you spend £5,000/month in UK your spendings here would be $10.000 for the same lifestyle. I don\'t know if i\'m right or not, it\'s just a wild guess.\r\n \r\nYou can search the forums for #prices and you might find some other informations.','58.6.249.164',973535652,0,0,0,0,1,'27f8b896cdae035f38353ab931c30fcf',''),(47,35,46,16,'RE: Money required to move (relocation) in Australia',0,223,'JhonnyB',1366119452,'Compared to most of the countries .. that\'s a lot ! How can you afford all that ?','58.6.249.164',973535652,0,0,0,0,1,'ba601e62cd3584eee63e7a232c4cb3f2',''),(48,35,46,16,'RE: Money required to move (relocation) in Australia',19,222,'Pops',1366122221,'well, everything it\'s hard at the beginning of course. \r\n\r\nIn Australia it\'s hard until you get an Australian job especially the job you are qualified yo do. After you get that Australian job, everything will seem so much cheaper. Australians in special like to complain a lot about the prices, but everyone can afford everything although it seems so expensive.\r\n\r\nFor example, last month my family spent almost $4.000 AUD on rent, food, some clothes, and utilities and i know it seems a lot, yea we even complain a bit, but that\'s manageable as we have earned about $7.000 AUD.\r\n\r\nSo all in all it\'s ok. The prices do scare everyone but it\'s ok once you earn Australian style :P','58.6.249.164',973535652,0,0,222,1366124476,1,'c1d43d6fab3a129fab6f576a993fe62c',''),(49,36,0,8,'Do i have to work when i will apply for a visa ?',0,223,'JhonnyB',1366167820,'So ? Do i  ?\r\n\r\nDo i have to work when i will apply for an Australian visa ? I\'m asking this because of the bad economy i am currently unemployed although i have 6 years experience as an architect.\r\n\r\nLooking forward for your answer','58.6.249.164',973535652,0,0,0,0,1,'64739eeebd66a62c27fcaabe22a92e69',''),(50,37,0,7,'How to pay your fees to TRA - Trades Recognition Australia',0,222,'Pops',1366168323,'first step: http://www.innovation.gov.au/tra\r\n\r\nsecond step: in the left vertical menu select \"Job Ready Program\"\r\n\r\nthird step: the last section of that webpage is called \"Applying for the Job Ready Program\". There you will find a link \"Online Portal\" which leads to https://extranet.deewr.gov.au/trades/Interface/Pages/Security/Logon.aspx which is a portal for paying some fees to a number of things including Migration Skill Assessment.\r\n\r\nTo make an payment , you have to create an account with your details. You have to  print the receipt and attach it to the front page of your application which you will have to send to #TRA for Migration Skill #Assessment. The pay is done in AUD (Australian Dollars). The conversion from your currency to AUD is done automatically. \r\n\r\n[b]Attention[/b]: the fee can be paid only with VISA (including visa electron) or American Express. Apparently there is no other option','58.6.249.164',973535652,0,0,0,0,1,'e8a0a1e0fa16a04258ef0679a366ae88',''),(51,36,49,8,'RE: Do i have to work when i will apply for a visa ?',0,224,'Andrew',1366213478,'Well, as stated in the[url=http://www.immigrationaustralia.info/points-test-table-2012-2013.thread] points test table for 2012 - 2013[/url], you don\'t need to be working at the time you submit an EOI or you are invited to apply for a visa as long as you have worked in the past 10 years.','58.6.249.164',973535652,0,0,224,1366213511,1,'426e31f02738090b2a7ad3848fc20895',''),(52,36,49,8,'RE: Do i have to work when i will apply for a visa ?',0,221,'Jay',1366254438,'Well, now with the 2012 changes in the immigration system you have more flexibility over this part. We don\'t know how long it will last so i think you should take this opportunity while you can','58.6.249.164',973535652,0,0,0,0,1,'e3e1b3af34c13bff882b540e5520573a',''),(53,38,0,10,'Traveling with an infant',0,222,'Pops',1366282231,'[size=medium]1. Take your pushchair right up to the aircraft door[/size]\r\n\r\nMost airlines these days let you do this, so don’t be tempted to check it in early and just rely on a baby carrier or sling. That way, if there is any delay, then your baby or toddler can have a really comfortable sleep, and your back will be buying you a coffee in thanks. Many airlines will also let you have your pushchair back as soon as you step off the plane at the other end. This is an absolute godsend and makes all the difference if you’ve gone a little over-the-top with buying too much Duty Free beforehand.\r\n\r\n[size=medium] 2. Take a night flight[/size]\r\n\r\nThis way, in theory, your kids will sleep for a large proportion of the flight because they will be tired. Even if you have a baby who is restless, your toddler should sleep more easily, meaning you only have one child to stay up with. If you catch a day flight, then you will almost certainly be up for the entire flight with both children (especially if your toddler no longer has daytime naps). Believe me, this works.\r\n\r\n[size=medium] 3. Arrange a stopover[/size]\r\n\r\nIf you are flying for more than 12 hours with children, I would strongly recommend stopping over for at least a few days at the refuelling stop. Not only does it make travel boredom more bearable (i.e. one 24 hour flight is much more horrific than two 12 hours flights!), it also helps to break up the jet lag, so that you can cope with it in easier-to-handle segments. And hopefully, by the time you get to your second destination, it will nearly have gone. It also means that you can try to arrange another night flight for your final leg, which wouldn’t be possible if you were doing it all in one go, and the kids should sleep the majority of the second night flight too.\r\n\r\n[size=medium] 4. Ask for a bulkhead seat[/size]\r\n\r\nDo this when booking so you can get a bassinet cot for your baby. Otherwise they will need to sit on your lap at all times, which can make eating meals difficult, especially if you’re travelling on your own. Even if you don’t have a baby, bulkhead seats offer more room for bags of kiddy essentials, and you don’t have to worry about your toddler kicking the seats of the people in front of you.\r\n\r\n[size=medium] 5. Lower your expectations[/size]\r\n\r\nOne of the most important things you can do is to mentally prepare yourself before you go. It will be horrendous, it will be long, it will be tiring, your kids won’t sleep as well as they do back home, they won’t want to eat when the meals are being served, and you definitely won’t get to watch an entire movie all the way through (although if you’re lucky, you might get to catch the end on the flight home). Lower your expectations and then you might just be pleasantly surprised. And keep telling yourself that, flights, like labour, will be over eventually too.\r\n\r\nGot it from this thread: http://www.emigrareaustralia.info/forum/transport-si-expedieri/calatoria-cu-copilul','58.6.249.164',973535652,0,0,0,0,1,'17e357bf2929a6154e96a36394b3d1cf',''),(54,39,0,12,'Hello everyone',0,222,'Pops',1366282468,'Hello everyone. My name is Adrian and i moved to Australia in 2012 from Romania, Europe.\r\n\r\nI\'m 27 and moved to Australia with my wife and my child. My wife was the main applicant - Architect.\r\n\r\nI couldn\'t assess my skills as i was a lawyer in back in Romania and the law system there it\'s not based on common law.','58.6.249.164',973535652,0,0,0,0,1,'344112307596c0995f88346cf970fe73',''),(55,40,0,38,'Australia and US issue warning over visa admin scams',0,226,'Ardesh',1366339198,'The American and Australian immigration authorities are warning expats looking for professional help and advice on visa requirements and applications to beware of crooks posing as immigration officials. \r\n\r\nAustralia’s Department of Immigration and Citizenship is citing reports that phone scammers are targeting the country’s international communities, identifying students and 457 visa holders and offering fixes for visa irregularities for a so-called penalty payment to an offshore bank. A DIAC spokesperson confirmed that the conmen are claiming visas are out of date and demanding an immediate payment backed by threats of prison and deportation. \r\n\r\nAnyone receiving such a call, the spokesperson added, should tell the caller they are aware of the scam and will be reported to the police. The American scams involve unauthorised immigration service practitioners out to rip off those needing help with US immigration procedures, and those targeted should remember that giving unauthorised immigration advice for a fee is against US law. \r\n\r\nThe United States Citizenship and immigration Service (USCIS) advises that taking unauthorised advice risks delaying your application, is unnecessarily expensive and may result in deportation. Its newly-launched Unauthorised Practice of Immigration Law initiative aims to combat scams by giving local community organisations, legal service specialists and applicants themselves the tools to protect themselves and their clients from illegal cons. \r\n\r\nAdvice being offered includes a list of well-known scams, a list of fully legal immigration service companies and help with filing applications. A USCIS spokesperson explained that if all potential immigrants take advantage of the advice offered, scammers would be forced out of business.\n[hr]\nBtw the article was taken from here: http://www.emigrate.co.uk/news/20130418-6626_immigration-authorities-crack-down-on-visa-scams','58.6.249.164',973535652,0,0,226,1366339221,1,'7e8b37449949bd9462510ed8acd855bd',''),(56,41,0,18,'tips and tricks for tracking, trapping and landing those elusive jobs',0,226,'Ardesh',1366379706,'Never focus on just one job, you must always have more jobs in the pipeline. This gives you more chances of success, reduces wasted time AND reduces feelings of disappointment\r\n\r\nExamine the job advert *very* carefully, and address each part of it thoroughly.\r\nOf course there are a few tricks to this as well.\r\n\r\nSome job ads have a simple description, but others have a job package to download.\r\nIt is the second type that we will focus on here.\r\n\r\nFollow all instructions to the letter (advert plus package) – make a checklist from the instructions, and double check it before applying\r\n\r\nCarefully note the submission deadline. This is VITAL, you WILL be rejected if you are 1 second late\r\n- Put a reminder in your calendar\r\n- Upload a day early, because your internet connection WILL fail when you are nearing the deadline\r\n\r\nMost job application packages have a list of Essential Criteria and Desirable Criteria.\r\n\r\n[size=medium]Essential criteria[/size]\r\n\r\nThese are things the employee says you must have to get the job.\r\nOK that sounds obvious, but in fact the employer may not be able to get someone who has EVERY attribute that they require, and so they may have to compromise and take someone less skilled.\r\n\r\nSo if you didn’t apply because you were lacking a skill, you may have missed your chance.\r\n[b]\r\nTrick 1[/b] - ADDRESS EVERY essential criterion. That doesn’t mean that you will MEET them all, it just means you must write SOMETHING POSITIVE about every requirement.\r\n\r\nE.g. an essential criterion might be, “PHP Programming skills”.\r\nIf you have never programmed in PHP, you should still ADDRESS the criterion\r\nBut don’t say “I don’t know how to program in PMP” – that is negative (bad)\r\n\r\nInstead be positive e.g\r\n“I am a fast learner and I am proficient in Java and C++ so I know I will master PHP in a short time”\r\n\r\nThat sounds positive, doesn’t it!\r\n\r\n[b]Trick 2[/b] – Address each PART of each question\r\n\r\nMany criteria are compound\r\nE.g.\r\n“Must have well developed analytical, programming and testing skills”\r\n\r\nThat is THREE parts, not one:\r\nMust have:\r\n1. well developed analytical skills\r\n2. well developed programming skills\r\n3. well developed testing skills\r\n\r\nSo you must address part 1, 2 and 3\r\n\r\n[b]Trick 3[/b] - Use the SAME wording AND order that the employer uses.\r\n\r\nWhy? It makes it easy from them to see you are a good match\r\n\r\ne.g. to address the above criterion\r\n\r\n“At ABC limited my well-developed analytical, programming and testing skills were often recognised by my managers and clients. I used my analytical skills when discussing requirements with the client, which I then programmed and tested. I have many emails from satisfied clients”\r\n\r\nThe reason for using the SAME wording and order is that when you apply for a position, initially the manager does NOT read your application.\r\n\r\nUsually applications are received by a more junior person, who may NOT know a lot about the job (and may not understand your answers)\r\n\r\nThat junior person will simply be given a table of the essential and desirable criteria, and a pile of job applications to check\r\n\r\nThe person will then score you on how well you match each criterion.\r\nIf you fail this test, you will probably NOT get an interview\r\n\r\nBut if you use the same words in the same order, it makes it very easy for the person to see you match!\r\n\r\n[b]Trick 4[/b] - ADDRESS every Desirable criterion\r\n\r\nPeople often say that you don’t need to address “Desirable criteria” but you do!\r\n\"Desirable” means that the employer desires (would really like) these too.\r\n\r\nSometimes if you are weak in one essential area, but strong in a desirable area, you may still get an interview\r\n\r\nAnd if two applicants are very evenly matched in the essential criteria, the desirable criteria may be consider to make the choice.\r\n\r\nAnd some “desirable criteria” are so easy to attain\r\n\r\nE.g.\r\n“Knowledge of Equal Opportunity Act”\r\nTo meet this one, read a booklet on the Act at the library','58.6.249.164',973535652,0,0,0,0,1,'56009878e2f9cdaf928958cc82b52874',''),(57,42,0,20,'RIP the Australian midsize ISP 2001-2013',0,227,'Mulfa',1366455030,'Got this from the Whirlpool web forums in Australia\r\n\r\nThe last few years have seen the last round of consolidation in the Australian ISP space. In that time, the broadband market saturated and the churn wars began, putting cost pressures on everyone as the ADSL ISP model changed from bringing people off dialup to having to take every customer you won off another broadband ISP. With the M2 announcement around Dodo and Eftel today almost all of the mid size independents are gone from the ADSL market that kicked off in 2001 with the launch of Telstra\'s ADSL wholesale service.\r\n\r\nI find myself inspired to write about those years, and I thought others might be interested in running over some of that ground with me.\r\n\r\nThe idea of this thread is not to bemoan the reduction in consumer choice, but to remember some names and pour one out for the dearly departed as well as recognise those who survived. I\'m also focussing on the consumer side of the market where the most vicious and public battles have always taken place. For former ISP staff like myself ISPland was a great place to start a career and to meet people who would define the direction we went in life.\r\n\r\nSo, without further ado lets kick it off.\r\n\r\nThe Winners – \r\n\r\nStill standing after 12 years of cutthroat competition and acquisition. Some of these companies have outgrown their garage beginnings to become employers of thousands with hundreds of millions in revenue. Others started big and ugly and over time remained big and ugly.\r\n\r\nI\'ve ranked them by revenue here because a lot of the claims around sub numbers are pretty hard to verify and meaningless anyway – I\'m sure plenty of ISP guys like me remember laughing at advertised subscriber numbers and wondering how many were dialup. It is a little unfair to compare a full spectrum business like Optus to a single product company like iiNet on revenue, but revenue and profitability have played a big part in who survived so I think it is relevant.\r\n\r\n1. Telstra\r\nFY12 Revenue – 25 billion or so.\r\n\r\nA long discussion about Telstra\'s role in the market for the last 12 years is outside the scope of this thread, but they started on top and ended on top.\r\n\r\n2. Optus\r\nFY12 Revenue – 9 billion or so.\r\n\r\nCame into the market with a government mandate to create competition. Rolled out an HFC network seemingly just to annoy Telstra and local councils, who found themselves with two crews of tree loppers coming through instead of one. Went through multiple changes of ownership through the dotcomm bust and ended up owned by Singtel. Most observers would agree that Singtel would go on to treat Optus with a fascinating sort of benign neglect – they never really seemed to have much use for Optus but it seemed to hum along and make money and so they let it go on with an occasional cost cutting spree. Continues to be the reliable number 2 through inertia and the strength of its mobile business.\r\n\r\n3. iiNet\r\nFY12 Revenue – 831 Million\r\n\r\nFrom a true garage geek beginning, iiNet has one of the most fascinating growth stories of the last twenty years. Always eager to acquire and grow, iiNet has come close to the edge a few times after severe Ozemail indigestion and a predatory TPG circling occasionally depressed share pricing. They seem to have moved past these concerns, acquiring strongly customer focussed businesses and remaining on a growth path. Like a lot of companies on this list, it remains to be seen if they can successfully diversify away from a broadband only play – FetchTV and iiNet mobile have yet to set the world on fire.\r\n\r\n4. TPG\r\nFY12 Revenue – 663 Million\r\n\r\nTPG deserves recognition as one of the most cost focussed businesses to come through the decade. Teoh\'s focus on costs was legendary, with stories of staff personal expenses being rejected by him personally as being unreasonable. They also seem to have benefitted from a close relationship with Telstra Wholesale that was used to keep wholesale costs under control, and kept Teoh from joining the chorus of criticism against Telstra. They have made smart investment decisions, buying undervalued companies to move into new markets (Soul) or keep costs down (Pipe). Never renowned as a customer service focussed company, they remained a provider of choice for both the $/GB crowd through highly aggressive pricing and the average punter through a highly visible marketing campaign.\r\n\r\n5. M2 \r\nFY12 Revenue – 393 Million\r\n\r\nAsk people five years ago whether this accumulation of failed businesses would where it is today, and I doubt you\'d get a positive answer. Rolling up many different companies over the years M2 has emerged as number five by revenue in the Australia markets, and seems to have done very well at absorbing marginally profitable or distinctly unprofitable companies into its business. If the Dodo and Eftel acquisitions come off they may even be able to move up and grow larger than TPG.\n[hr]\nOkay so lets run through those who didnt quite make it. Some companies were bought, some ran into business problems and others just moved out of the market. Its pretty hard to get reliable information on subscriber numbers or revenue for most of these companies so the list is presented in no particular order.\n\n The Fallen \n\nChariot\n\nAn SA dialup ISP that crossed into the world of ADSL with some success. Acquired by TPG in 2007 for 4.5 million, but seems to have maintained a semi independent brand and support team.\n\naaNet\n\nRolled into Eftel in 2006 or 2007 amongst great confusion and Telstra legal action. Feared by Telstra WCTA consultants everywhere after some drama between them and Exetel caused thousands of churns overnight.\n\nEftel\n\nNotable as one of the smaller companies that installed competitive DSLAMs, and fought hard to maintain their independence amongst activist shareholders and limited scale. Eventually reverse acquired by ClubTelco in 2011.\n\nComindico\n\nFamous for offering unlimited ADSL plans up to 2004 through its network of wholesalers, it stopped offering these plans and was acquired by Soul within the month. Also famous as the other company backed by Packer, albeit to less of a degree than OneTel\n\nAdam Internet\n\nMay end up in the last man standing category if the acquisition fails, but looks to have been acquired by Telstra for now. Completely focussed on the SA market to the joy of Adelaide Amiga fans everywhere, the smaller Adelaide market provided a safe growing place for Adam and hometown rival Internode\n\nDart Internet\n\nIn the heady days of 2003, Dart had some of the best 512k plans available and an active Whirlpool presence. Ran into trouble at some point in 2004 and was eventually firesaled for $225k.\n\niPrimus\n\nA perfect example of the mid size ISPs I\'m talking about. Built its own fibre networks, its own DSLAMs and its own data centres with an east coast focus. CEO Ravi Bhatia was a vocal advocate for competitive carriers and iPrimus\'s foreign ownership gave us the spectacle of the US trade representive rolling in to blast Telstra every 12 months. Ultimately though there didn\'t really seem to be a place for iPrimus in the market, and they were picked up by M2.\n\nNetspace\n\nAnother middle tier ISP. Built a strong Victorian market presence, with their own data centre and DSLAM network. Never acquired the scale or inclination to go acquiring companies, was eventually bought by iiNet in 2010 as the market shifted away from mid size independent players.\n\nWestnet\n\nWith probably the strongest customer service reputation in the industry, Westnet was acquired by iiNet in 2008 but maintained as a seperate brand. Notable for having an evil twin, The Other Westnet.\n\nInternode\n\nThe defining middle market innovative independent ISP, the Internode story is the story of this market segment. Innovative technical leadership and a strong customer focus allowed them to grow rapidly in the mid 00\'s and punch well above their own weight in market presence and voice. Just as with the rest of the market, there didn\'t seem to be a place for them in the new pre NBN world and were acquired in 2011 by iiNet.\n\n The Last Man Standing \n\nExetel\n\nExetel remains as the last significantly sized independent ISP in Australia. Anyone who followed John Linton\'s blog will not find this surprising – Exetel focussed on process automation and outsourcing to drive costs down with a focus that rivalled TPG. Even more so than social media active companies like Internode and iiNet, the Exetel blog gives us a view into the realities of middle tier ISP life and is required reading for anyone with an interest in the market.\n\n Why all these words about nothing \n\nAs you can see, my knowledge is incomplete. If anyone has any stories to share of the industry in the last 12 years, wants to pour one out for their favourite ISP of 2004, any significant ISPs I have missed or anything else that springs to mind then please contribute. If no one else has anything to say then and this is only of interest to me then that is fine too.','58.6.249.164',973535652,0,0,227,1366455055,1,'e3d289918f6c6463ae9d050f884d6068',''),(58,42,57,20,'RE: RIP the Australian midsize ISP 2001-2013',0,226,'Ardesh',1366463759,'Verry nice read,\n\nThank you','58.6.249.164',973535652,0,0,0,0,1,'28b6c58bc23e9ef7ae8fdc582c1e800f',''),(62,44,60,25,'RE: The most important links for new immigrants in Australia',0,221,'Jay',1366472351,'[url=http://www.austrade.gov.au/]Austrade - business in Australia[/url]','58.6.249.164',973535652,0,0,0,0,1,'7cdca1d2a9b4f8ce52bff331656ae275',''),(63,46,0,20,'Ten tips for surviving long term house guests',0,228,'Pulp',1366472677,'Got this from [url=http://www.mumsgone2aus.com/2010/12/20/ten-tips-for-surviving-long-term-house-guests/#comments]momsgone2aus.com[/url]\r\n\r\nA natural consequence of moving to Australia is that you can expect frequent and long term house guests. This is particularly true if you’re relocating from Europe, and are leaving close family and friends in your country of origin.\r\n\r\nAt chateau Mum’s gone 2 Aus we’ve had several visitors already, but are about to receive our most eagerly awaited, and long term guests…the grandparents (the children’s that is, not Mum’s!). The grandparents are staying for six weeks, so we’re fortunate to be able to spend quality time together during the festive season and long school holidays.\r\n\r\nNaturally, sharing your home with other people takes some getting used to. Lesley Snell, from Northern Beaches Know-How understands what it’s like to receive such lovely, long term guests (see how careful I’m being not to offend!!).\r\n\r\nLesley has relocated several times with her family (three children and husband); she recently left these top tips on the Mum’s gone 2 Aus facebook page. Thanks Lesley for letting me repeat them here.\r\nTen tips for surviving long term house guests\r\n\r\n1. Provide visitors with two sets of bedding and bath towels so they can change their bed when it suits them.\r\n\r\n2. Show them how to use your washing machine.\r\n\r\n3. Say “Yes please that would be great” to anything they offer to do.\r\n\r\n4. Take advantage of in-built babysitters.\r\n\r\n5. If you have a dishwasher, encourage visitors to load it and don’t worry if it’s not quite the way you would do it.\r\n\r\n6. Provide visitors with their own hairdryer.\r\n\r\n7. Give each other space, you don’t have to be together all of the time.\r\n\r\n8. Give visitors a front door key.\r\n\r\n9. Have fun and create memories.\r\n\r\n10. If you don’t have one already get yourself a guest book and start a tradition that anyone who sleeps over signs the book and adds comments, it’ll be a great keepsake. Fishpond stock a simple hardcover guest book with 96 pages for $21: Sea Foam Guest Book.\r\n\r\nFinally, a bonus tip from Mum…if you’ve got preschool children, be cautious about discussing your visitors too early. My eldest is so excited about his grandparent’s arrival we’ve had to stop talking about it for a few days, Mum can’t stand all the bouncing!','58.6.249.164',973535652,0,0,0,0,1,'dddd0ca022744a38f03d54cb07e8fc3a',''),(60,44,0,25,'The most important links for new immigrants in Australia',0,224,'Andrew',1366466748,'These are the most important links i found in the immigration process to Australia\r\n\r\n[list]\r\n[*][url=http://www.immi.gov.au/]DIAC - Department of Immigration and Citizenship[/url]\r\n[*][url=http://www.immi.gov.au/allforms/]DIAC - All forms[/url]\r\n[*][url=http://www.daff.gov.au/aqis/travel/entering-australia/cant-take]What can and can\'t you bring into Australia[/url]\r\n[*][url=http://www.ato.gov.au/]Australian Taxation Office[/url]\r\n[*][url=http://www.studyinaustralia.gov.au/Sia/en/Home.htm]Study in Australia[/url]\r\n[*][url=http://www.ozforex.com.au/]Exchange office very very good[/url]\r\n[*][url=http://www.mrt-rrt.gov.au/]Migration Review Tribunal[/url]\r\n[*][url=http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australia]About Australia - Wikipedia[/url]\r\n[*][url=http://austimelines.com/CurrentVisas.aspx]Australia migration timelines[/url]\r\n[*][url=http://www.seek.com.au/]Seek - the biggest jobs website in Australia[/url]\r\n[*][url=http://www.domain.com.au/]Buy/Rent houses in Australia - Domain[/url]\r\n[*][url=http://www.realestate.com.au/]Buy/Rent houses in Australia - RealEstate[/url]\r\n[*][url=http://www.ebay.com.au/]eBay Australia[/url]\r\n[*][url=http://www.immi.gov.au/tis]TIS National (Translating and Interpreting Service) [/url]\r\n[*][url=http://www.citizenship.gov.au/]Australian Citizenship[/url]\r\n[*][url=http://www.qld.gov.au/]Official website of Queensland[/url]\r\n[*][url=http://www.nsw.gov.au/]Official website of New South Wales[/url]\r\n[*][url=http://wa.gov.au/]Official website of Western Australia[/url]\r\n[*][url=http://www.vic.gov.au/]Official website of Victoria[/url]\r\n[*][url=http://www.act.gov.au/]Official website of Australian Capital Territory - ACT[/url]\r\n[*][url=http://www.sa.gov.au/]Official website of South Australia[/url]\r\n[*][url=http://www.nt.gov.au/]Official website of Northern Territory[/url]\r\n[*][url=http://www.tas.gov.au/]Official website of Tasmania[/url]\r\n[/list]\r\n\r\nPlease feel free to add yours','58.6.249.164',973535652,0,0,0,0,1,'cdfd8dc3b9b5d5150fb64ffb210d3482',''),(64,39,54,12,'RE: Hello everyone',0,230,'pantha',1366540444,'Hello ppl,\n\nI\'m Alexander from Romania. Hope well have a good talk here :)','58.6.249.164',973535652,0,0,0,0,1,'39f5b84792534fba0716ca55fe73a9c9',''),(65,47,0,33,'Recognised countries for the driver\'s licence',0,230,'pantha',1366541239,'If you hold a driver\'s licence from a ‘recognised country’ and the licence has not expired by more than 12 months, when applying for a WA licence: \r\nYou are exempt from taking the computerised theory test on the road rules \r\nYou may be exempt from the requirement to undertake a practical driving assessment. \r\nFor eligibility, please see notes/key below.\r\n[b]\r\nRecognised countries include the following:[/b]\r\n[list]\r\n[*]Austria \r\n[*]Belgium \r\n[*]Bosnia-Herzegovina ‡ \r\n[*]Canada \r\n[*]Croatia \r\n[*]Denmark \r\n[*]Finland \r\n[*]France \r\n[*]Germany \r\n[*]Greece \r\n[*]Guernsey \r\n[*]Ireland \r\n[*]Isle of Man § \r\n[*]Italy \r\n[*]Japan \r\n[*]Jersey \r\n[*]Luxembourg \r\n[*]Malta † \r\n[*]Netherlands \r\n[*]New Zealand \r\n[*]Norway \r\n[*]Portugal \r\n[*]Singapore \r\n[*]Spain \r\n[*]Sweden \r\n[*]Switzerland \r\n[*]United Kingdom \r\n[*]United States of America\r\n[/list]\r\n\r\nNotes/key:\r\n\r\n‡  Recognised for new applications from 1 March 2013\r\n§  Recognised if your Isle of Man licence was issued on or after 1 November 1991\r\n†  Recognised if your Malta licence was issued on or after 2 January 2004.\r\n\r\n[b]Experienced driver recognised country[/b]\r\n\r\nOn 1 September 2012 Western Australia adopted a new ‘experienced driver’ recognised country category. If your driver licence was issued by an ‘experienced driver’ recognised country and you are 25 years of age or older, WA will recognise your overseas driving experience. (For eligibility, please see notes/key below)\r\n\r\nUpon application for the grant of a WA driver’s licence you will be exempt from the theory and practical assessments (car and motorcycle only), provided your overseas driver licence has not expired by more than 12 months.\r\n\r\nIf you hold a driver licence from an ‘experienced driver recognised’ country and you are under 25 years of age you will be required to undertake and pass the theory and practical driving tests prior to the grant of a WA driver’s licence. \r\nExperienced driver recognised country list:\r\n[list]\r\n[*]Bulgaria ‡ \r\n[*]Cyprus ‡ \r\n[*]Czech Republic « \r\n[*]Estonia « \r\n[*]Hong Kong « \r\n[*]Hungary ‡ \r\n[*]Latvia ‡ \r\n[*]Lithuania ‡ \r\n[*]Poland ‡ \r\n[*]Republic of Korea « \r\n[*]Romania ‡ \r\n[*]Slovakia ‡ \r\n[*]Slovenia ‡ \r\n[*]South Africa ‡ \r\n[*]Taiwan «\r\n[/list]\r\n\r\nNotes/key:\r\n\r\n‡ Recognised for new applications from 1 March 2013\r\n« Recognised for new applications from 1 September 2012\r\n\r\n[b]Driver from a non-recognised driver country[/b]\r\n\r\nNon-Recognised countries are countries that are assessed as not meeting the minimum requirements of the National Australian Standard. Applicants from these countries must undertake and pass both the practical assessment and the theory tests.\r\n\r\n[b]Laws about driving legally in Western Australia[/b]\r\n\r\n The fact sheet below provides information on driving legally in Western Australia (WA). It also provides an overview on how to apply for a WA driver’s licence. More detailed information is provided below. \r\n\r\n[b]Permanent visa holders[/b]\r\n\r\nIf you hold a permanent visa, you can continue to drive on your overseas licence until